# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fuel-cell-chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] An **electrocatalyst** is a catalyst that participates in electrochemical reactions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Electrocatalysts are a specific form of catalysts that function at electrode surfaces or, most commonly, may be the electrode surface itself.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] An electrocatalyst can be heterogeneous such as a platinized electrode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Homogeneous electrocatalysts, which are soluble, assist in transferring electrons between the electrode and reactants, and/or facilitate an intermediate chemical transformation described by an overall half reaction.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Major challenges in electrocatalysts focus on fuel cells.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] An electrocatalyst lowers the activation energy required for an electrochemical reaction.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Some electrocatalysts change the potential at which oxidation and reduction processes occur.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] In other cases, an electrocatalyst can impart selectivity by favoring specific chemical interaction at an electrode surface.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Given that electrochemical reactions occur when electrons are passed from one chemical species to another, favorable interactions at an electrode surface increase the likelihood of electrochemical transformations occurring, thus reducing the potential required to achieve these transformations.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Electrocatalysts can be evaluated according to activity, stability, and selectivity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] The activity of electrocatalysts can be assessed quantitatively by the current density is generated, and therefore how fast a reaction is taking place, for a given applied potential.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] This relationship is described with the Tafel equation.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] In assessing the stability of electrocatalysts, the a key parameter is turnover number (TON).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] The selectivity of electrocatalysts refers to the product distribution.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Selectivity can be quantitatively assessed through a selectivity coefficient, which compares the response of the material to the desired analyte or substrate with the response to other interferents.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] In many electrochemical systems, including galvanic cells, fuel cells and various forms of electrolytic cells, a drawback is that they can suffer from high activation barriers.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] The energy diverted to overcome these activation barriers is transformed into heat.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] In most exothermic combustion reactions this heat would simply propagate the reaction catalytically.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] In a redox reaction, this heat is a useless byproduct lost to the system.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] The extra energy required to overcome kinetic barriers is usually described in terms of low faradaic efficiency and high overpotentials.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] In these systems, each of the two electrodes and its associated half-cell would require its own specialized electrocatalyst.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Half-reactions involving multiple steps, multiple electron transfers, and the evolution or consumption of gases in their overall chemical transformations, will often have considerable kinetic barriers.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Furthermore, there is often more than one possible reaction at the surface of an electrode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] For example, during the electrolysis of water, the anode can oxidize water through a two electron process to hydrogen peroxide or a four electron process to oxygen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] The presence of an electrocatalyst could facilitate either of the reaction pathways.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] A homogeneous electrocatalyst is one that is present in the same phase of matter as the reactants, for example, a water-soluble coordination complex catalyzing an electrochemical conversion in solution.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] This technology is not practiced commercially, but is of research interest.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Many coordination complexes catalyze electrochemical reactions, although few have achieved commercial success.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Well investigated processes include the hydrogen evolution reaction.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] There is much interest in replacing traditional chemical catalysis with electrocatalysis.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] In such a scheme electrons supplied by an electrode are reagents.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] The topic is a theme within the area of green energy, because the electrons can be sourced from renewable resources.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Several conversions that use hydrogen gas could be transformed into electrochemical processes that use protons.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] This technology remains economically noncompetitive.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Another example is found in the area of nitrogen fixation.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] The ammonia represents an energy source since it is combustable.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] In this way electrification can be seen as a means for energy storage.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Another process attracting much effort is the electrochemical reduction of carbon dioxide.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Some enzymes can function as electrocatalysts.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Nitrogenase, an enzyme that contains a MoFe cluster, can be leveraged to fix atmospheric nitrogen, i.e. convert nitrogen gas into molecules such as ammonia.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Immobilizing the protein onto an electrode surface and employing an electron mediator greatly improves the efficiency of this process.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] The effectiveness of bioelectrocatalysts generally depends on the ease of electron transport between the active site of the enzyme and the electrode surface.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Other enzymes provide insight for the development of synthetic catalysts.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] For example, formate dehydrogenase, a nickel-containing enzyme, has inspired the development of synthetic complexes with similar molecular structures for use in CO2 reduction.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Microbial fuel cells are another way that biological systems can be leveraged for electrocatalytic applications.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Microbial-based systems leverage the metabolic pathways of an entire organism, rather than the activity of a specific enzyme, meaning that they can catalyze a broad range of chemical reactions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Microbial fuel cells can derive current from the oxidation of substrates such as glucose, and be leveraged for processes such as CO2 reduction.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] A heterogeneous electrocatalyst is one that is present in a different phase of matter from the reactants, for example, a solid surface catalyzing a reaction in solution.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Different types of heterogeneous electrocatalyst materials are shown above in green.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] The nature of the electrocatalyst surface determines some properties of the reaction including rate and selectivity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Electrocatalysis can occur at the surface of some bulk materials, such as platinum metal.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Bulk metal surfaces of gold have been employed for the decomposition methanol for hydrogen production.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Water electrolysis is conventionally conducted at inert bulk metal electrodes such as platinum or iridium.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] The activity of an electrocatalyst can be tuned with a chemical modification, commonly obtained by alloying two or more metals.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] This is due to a change in the electronic structure, especially in the d band which is considered to be responsible for the catalytic properties of noble metals.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] A variety of nanoparticle materials have been demonstrated to promote various electrochemical reactions, although none have been commercialized.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] These catalysts can be tuned with respect to their size and shape, as well as the surface strain.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Also, higher reaction rates can be achieved by precisely controlling the arrangement of surface atoms: indeed, in nanometric systems, the number of available reaction sites is a better parameter than the exposed surface area in order to estimate electrocatalytic activity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Sites are the positions where the reaction could take place; the likelihood of a reaction to occur in a certain site depends on the electronic structure of the catalyst, which determines the adsorption energy of the reactants together with many other variables not yet fully clarified.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] According to the TSK model, the catalyst surface atoms can be classified as terrace, step or kink atoms according to their position, each characterized by a different coordination number.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] In principle, atoms with lower coordination number (kinks and defects) tend to be more reactive and therefore adsorb the reactants more easily: this may promote kinetics but could also depress it if the adsorbing species isn't the reactant, thus inactivating the catalyst.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Advances in nanotechnology make it possible to surface engineer the catalyst so that just some desired crystal planes are exposed to reactants, maximizing the number of effective reaction sites for the desired reaction.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] To date, a generalized surface dependence mechanism cannot be formulated since every surface effect is strongly reaction-specific.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] A few classifications of reactions based on their surface dependence have been proposed but there are still many exceptions that do not fall into them.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] The interest in reducing as much as possible the costs of the catalyst for electrochemical processes led to the use of fine catalyst powders since the specific surface area increases as the average particle size decreases.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] For instance, most common PEM fuel cells and electrolyzers design is based on a polymeric membrane charged in platinum nanoparticles as an electrocatalyst (the so-called platinum black).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Carbon nanotubes and graphene-based materials can be used as electrocatalysts.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] The carbon surfaces of graphene and carbon nanotubes are well suited to the adsorption of many chemical species, which can promote certain electrocatalytic reactions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] In addition, their conductivity means they are good electrode materials.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Carbon nanotubes have a very high surface area, maximizing surface sites at which electrochemical transformations can occur.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Graphene can also serve as a platform for constructing composites with other kinds of nanomaterials such as single atom catalysts.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Because of their conductivity, carbon-based materials can potentially replace metal electrodes to perform metal-free electrocatalysis.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Metal—organic frameworks (MOFs), especially conductive frameworks, can be used as electrocatalysts for processes such as CO2 reduction and water splitting.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] MOFs provide potential active sites at both metal centers and organic ligand sites.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] They can also be functionalized, or encapsulate other materials such as nanoparticles.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] MOFs can also be combined with carbon-based materials to form electrocatalysts.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Covalent organic frameworks (COFs), particularly those that contain metals, can also serve as electrocatalysts.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] COFs constructed from cobalt porphyrins demonstrated the ability to reduce carbon dioxide to carbon monoxide.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] However, many MOFs are known unstable in chemical and electrochemical conditions, making it difficult to tell if MOFs are actually catalysts or precatalysts.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] The real active sites of MOFs during electrocatalysis need to be analyzed comprehensively.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Hydrogen and oxygen can be combined through by the use of a fuel cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] In this process, the reaction is broken into two half reactions which occur at separate electrodes.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] In this situation the reactant's energy is directly converted to electricity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Useful energy can be obtained from the thermal heat of this reaction through an internal combustion engine with an upper efficiency of 60% (for compression ratio of 10 and specific heat ratio of 1.4) based on the Otto thermodynamic cycle.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] It is also possible to combine the hydrogen and oxygen through redox mechanism as in the case of a fuel cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] In this process, the reaction is broken into two half-reactions which occur at separate electrodes.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] The standard reduction potential of hydrogen is defined as 0V, and frequently referred to as the standard hydrogen electrode (SHE).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Electrocatalysis for CO2 reduction is not practiced commercially but remains a topic of research.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] The reduction of CO2 into useable products is a potential way to combat climate change.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Electrocatalysts can promote the reduction of carbon dioxide into methanol and other useful fuel and stock chemicals.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] The most valuable reduction products of CO2 are those that have a higher energy content, meaning that they can be reused as fuels.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Thus, catalyst development focuses on the production of products such as methane and methanol.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Homogeneous catalysts, such as enzymes and synthetic coordination complexes have been employed for this purpose.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] A variety of nanomaterials have also been studied for CO2 reduction, including carbon-based materials and framework materials.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Aqueous solutions of methanol can decompose into CO2 hydrogen gas, and water.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Although this process is thermodynamically favored, the activation barrier is extremely high, so in practice this reaction is not typically observed.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] However, electrocatalysts can speed up this reaction greatly, making methanol a possible route to hydrogen storage for fuel cells.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Electrocatalysts such as gold, platinum, and various carbon-based materials have been shown to effectively catalyze this process.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] An electrocatalyst of platinum and rhodium on carbon backed tin-dioxide nanoparticles can break carbon bonds at room temperature with only carbon dioxide as a by-product, so that ethanol can be oxidized into the necessary hydrogen ions and electrons required to create electricity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Electrocatalysts are used to promote certain chemical reactions to obtain synthetic products.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Graphene and graphene oxides have shown promise as electrocatalytic materials for synthesis.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Electrocatalytic methods also have potential for polymer synthesis.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Electrocatalytic synthesis reactions can be performed under a constant current, constant potential, or constant cell-voltage conditions, depending on the scale and purpose of the reaction.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] Water treatment systems often require the degradation of hazardous compounds.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/electrocatalyst] These treatment processes are dubbed Advanced oxidation processes, and are key in destroying byproducts from disinfection, pesticides, and other hazardous compound.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] A **fuel cell** is an electrochemical cell that converts the chemical energy of a fuel (often hydrogen) and an oxidizing agent (often oxygen) into electricity through a pair of redox reactions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Fuel cells are different from most batteries in requiring a continuous source of fuel and oxygen (usually from air) to sustain the chemical reaction, whereas in a battery the chemical energy usually comes from substances that are already present in the battery.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Fuel cells can produce electricity continuously for as long as fuel and oxygen are supplied.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The first fuel cells were invented by Sir William Grove in 1838.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The first commercial use of fuel cells came almost a century later following the invention of the hydrogen–oxygen fuel cell by Francis Thomas Bacon in 1932.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The alkaline fuel cell, also known as the Bacon fuel cell after its inventor, has been used in NASA space programs since the mid-1960s to generate power for satellites and space capsules.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Since then, fuel cells have been used in many other applications.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Fuel cells are used for primary and backup power for commercial, industrial and residential buildings and in remote or inaccessible areas.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] They are also used to power fuel cell vehicles, including forklifts, automobiles, buses, trains, boats, motorcycles, and submarines.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] There are many types of fuel cells, but they all consist of an anode, a cathode, and an electrolyte that allows ions, often positively charged hydrogen ions (protons), to move between the two sides of the fuel cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] At the anode, a catalyst causes the fuel to undergo oxidation reactions that generate ions (often positively charged hydrogen ions) and electrons.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The ions move from the anode to the cathode through the electrolyte.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] At the same time, electrons flow from the anode to the cathode through an external circuit, producing direct current electricity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] At the cathode, another catalyst causes ions, electrons, and oxygen to react, forming water and possibly other products.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Fuel cells are classified by the type of electrolyte they use and by the difference in start-up time ranging from 1 second for proton-exchange membrane fuel cells (PEM fuel cells, or PEMFC) to 10 minutes for solid oxide fuel cells (SOFC).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] A related technology is flow batteries, in which the fuel can be regenerated by recharging.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Individual fuel cells produce relatively small electrical potentials, about 0.7 volts, so cells are "stacked", or placed in series, to create sufficient voltage to meet an application's requirements.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] In addition to electricity, fuel cells produce water vapor, heat and, depending on the fuel source, very small amounts of nitrogen dioxide and other emissions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] PEMFC cells generally produce fewer nitrogen oxides than SOFC cells: they operate at lower temperatures, use hydrogen as fuel, and limit the diffusion of nitrogen into the anode via the proton exchange membrane, which forms NOx.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The energy efficiency of a fuel cell is generally between 40 and 60%; however, if waste heat is captured in a cogeneration scheme, efficiencies of up to 85% can be obtained.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The first references to hydrogen fuel cells appeared in 1838.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] In a letter dated October 1838 but published in the December 1838 edition of *The London and Edinburgh Philosophical Magazine and Journal of Science*, Welsh physicist and barrister Sir William Grove wrote about the development of his first crude fuel cells.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] He used a combination of sheet iron, copper, and porcelain plates, and a solution of sulphate of copper and dilute acid.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] In a letter to the same publication written in December 1838 but published in June 1839, German physicist Christian Friedrich Schönbein discussed the first crude fuel cell that he had invented.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] His letter discussed the current generated from hydrogen and oxygen dissolved in water.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Grove later sketched his design, in 1842, in the same journal.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The fuel cell he made used similar materials to today's phosphoric acid fuel cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] In 1932, English engineer Francis Thomas Bacon successfully developed a 5 kW stationary fuel cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] NASA used the alkaline fuel cell (AFC), also known as the Bacon fuel cell after its inventor, from the mid-1960s.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Thomas Grubb, a chemist working for the General Electric Company (GE), further modified the original fuel cell design by using a sulphonated polystyrene ion-exchange membrane as the electrolyte.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Three years later another GE chemist, Leonard Niedrach, devised a way of depositing platinum onto the membrane, which served as a catalyst for the necessary hydrogen oxidation and oxygen reduction reactions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] This became known as the "Grubb-Niedrach fuel cell".
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] GE went on to develop this technology with NASA and McDonnell Aircraft, leading to its use during Project Gemini.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] This was the first commercial use of a fuel cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] In 1959, a team led by Harry Ihrig built a 15 kW fuel cell tractor for Allis-Chalmers, which was demonstrated across the U.S. at state fairs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] This system used potassium hydroxide as the electrolyte and compressed hydrogen and oxygen as the reactants.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Later in 1959, Bacon and his colleagues demonstrated a practical five-kilowatt unit capable of powering a welding machine.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] In the 1960s, Pratt & Whitney licensed Bacon's U.S. patents for use in the U.S. space program to supply electricity and drinking water (hydrogen and oxygen being readily available from the spacecraft tanks).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] UTC Power was the first company to manufacture and commercialize a large, stationary fuel cell system for use as a cogeneration power plant in hospitals, universities and large office buildings.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] In recognition of the fuel cell industry and America's role in fuel cell development, the United States Senate recognized October 8, 2015 as National Hydrogen and Fuel Cell Day, passing S.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The date was chosen in recognition of the atomic weight of hydrogen (1.008).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Fuel cells come in many varieties; however, they all work in the same general manner.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] They are made up of three adjacent segments: the anode, the electrolyte, and the cathode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Two chemical reactions occur at the interfaces of the three different segments.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The net result of the two reactions is that fuel is consumed, water or carbon dioxide is created, and an electric current is created, which can be used to power electrical devices, normally referred to as the load.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] At the anode a catalyst ionizes the fuel, turning the fuel into a positively charged ion and a negatively charged electron.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The electrolyte is a substance specifically designed so ions can pass through it, but the electrons cannot.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The freed electrons travel through a wire creating an electric current.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The ions travel through the electrolyte to the cathode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Once reaching the cathode, the ions are reunited with the electrons and the two react with a third chemical, usually oxygen, to create water or carbon dioxide.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] A typical fuel cell produces a voltage from 0.6 to 0.7 V at a full-rated load.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] To deliver the desired amount of energy, the fuel cells can be combined in series to yield higher voltage, and in parallel to allow a higher current to be supplied.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Such a design is called a *fuel cell stack*.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The cell surface area can also be increased, to allow higher current from each cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] In the archetypical hydrogen–oxide proton-exchange membrane fuel cell (PEMFC) design, a proton-conducting polymer membrane (typically nafion) contains the electrolyte solution that separates the anode and cathode sides.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] This was called a *solid polymer electrolyte fuel cell* (*SPEFC*) in the early 1970s, before the proton-exchange mechanism was well understood.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] On the anode side, hydrogen diffuses to the anode catalyst where it later dissociates into protons and electrons.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] These protons often react with oxidants causing them to become what are commonly referred to as multi-facilitated proton membranes.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The protons are conducted through the membrane to the cathode, but the electrons are forced to travel in an external circuit (supplying power) because the membrane is electrically insulating.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] On the cathode catalyst, oxygen molecules react with the electrons (which have traveled through the external circuit) and protons to form water.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] In addition to this pure hydrogen type, there are hydrocarbon fuels for fuel cells, including diesel, methanol (*see:* direct-methanol fuel cells and indirect methanol fuel cells) and chemical hydrides.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The waste products with these types of fuel are carbon dioxide and water.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] When hydrogen is used, the CO2 is released when methane from natural gas is combined with steam, in a process called steam methane reforming, to produce the hydrogen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] This can take place in a different location to the fuel cell, potentially allowing the hydrogen fuel cell to be used indoors—for example, in forklifts.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] 5. the necessary hardware such as current collectors and gaskets.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The materials used for different parts of the fuel cells differ by type.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The bipolar plates may be made of different types of materials, such as, metal, coated metal, graphite, flexible graphite, C–C composite, carbon–polymer composites etc.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The membrane electrode assembly (MEA) is referred to as the heart of the PEMFC and is usually made of a proton-exchange membrane sandwiched between two catalyst-coated carbon papers.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Platinum and/or similar types of noble metals are usually used as the catalyst for PEMFC, and these can be contaminated by carbon monoxide, necessitating a relatively pure hydrogen fuel.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The electrolyte could be a polymer membrane.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] per kilowatt could be achieved, assuming volume production of 500,000 units per year.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Many companies are working on techniques to reduce cost in a variety of ways including reducing the amount of platinum needed in each individual cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] ) in platinum usage without reduction in performance.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] , which are less than 1% the cost of platinum and are of equal or superior performance.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] A recently published article demonstrated how the environmental burdens change when using carbon nanotubes as carbon substrate for platinum.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] In this type of fuel cell, the membrane must be hydrated, requiring water to be evaporated at precisely the same rate that it is produced.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] If water is evaporated too quickly, the membrane dries, the resistance across it increases, and eventually, it will crack, creating a gas "short circuit" where hydrogen and oxygen combine directly, generating heat that will damage the fuel cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] If the water is evaporated too slowly, the electrodes will flood, preventing the reactants from reaching the catalyst and stopping the reaction.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Just as in a combustion engine, a steady ratio between the reactant and oxygen is necessary to keep the fuel cell operating efficiently.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] O reaction is highly exothermic, so a large quantity of heat is generated within the fuel cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] typically require more than 40,000 hours of reliable operation at a temperature of −35 to 40 °C (−31 to 104 °F), while automotive fuel cells require a 5,000-hour lifespan (the equivalent of 240,000 km or 150,000 miles) under extreme temperatures.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Automotive engines must also be able to start reliably at −30 °C (−22 °F) and have a high power-to-volume ratio (typically 2.5 kW/L).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Phosphoric acid fuel cells (PAFCs) were first designed and introduced in 1961 by G.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] In these cells, phosphoric acid is used as a non-conductive electrolyte to pass protons from the anode to the cathode and to force electrons to travel from anode to cathode through an external electrical circuit.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] These cells commonly work in temperatures of 150 to 200 °C.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] This high temperature will cause heat and energy loss if the heat is not removed and used properly.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] This heat can be used to produce steam for air conditioning systems or any other thermal energy-consuming system.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Using this heat in cogeneration can enhance the efficiency of phosphoric acid fuel cells from 40 to 50% to about 80%.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Since the proton production rate on the anode is small, platinum is used as a catalyst to increase this ionization rate.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] A key disadvantage of these cells is the use of an acidic electrolyte.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] This increases the corrosion or oxidation of components exposed to phosphoric acid.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Solid acid fuel cells (SAFCs) are characterized by the use of a solid acid material as the electrolyte.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] At low temperatures, solid acids have an ordered molecular structure like most salts.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] At warmer temperatures (between 140 and 150 °C for CsHSO4), some solid acids undergo a phase transition to become highly disordered "superprotonic" structures, which increases conductivity by several orders of magnitude.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] SAFC systems use cesium dihydrogen phosphate (CsH2PO4) and have demonstrated lifetimes in the thousands of hours.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The alkaline fuel cell (AFC) or hydrogen-oxygen fuel cell was designed and first demonstrated publicly by Francis Thomas Bacon in 1959.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] It was used as a primary source of electrical energy in the Apollo space program.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The cell consists of two porous carbon electrodes impregnated with a suitable catalyst such as Pt, Ag, CoO, etc.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The space between the two electrodes is filled with a concentrated solution of KOH or NaOH which serves as an electrolyte.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] H2 gas and O2 gas are bubbled into the electrolyte through the porous carbon electrodes.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Thus the overall reaction involves the combination of hydrogen gas and oxygen gas to form water.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The cell runs continuously until the reactant's supply is exhausted.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] This type of cell operates efficiently in the temperature range 343–413 K (70 -140 °C) and provides a potential of about 0.9 V.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Alkaline anion exchange membrane fuel cell (AAEMFC) is a type of AFC which employs a solid polymer electrolyte instead of aqueous potassium hydroxide (KOH) and it is superior to aqueous AFC.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Solid oxide fuel cells (SOFCs) use a solid material, most commonly a ceramic material called yttria-stabilized zirconia (YSZ), as the electrolyte.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Because SOFCs are made entirely of solid materials, they are not limited to the flat plane configuration of other types of fuel cells and are often designed as rolled tubes.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] They require high operating temperatures (800–1000 °C) and can be run on a variety of fuels including natural gas.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] SOFCs are unique because negatively charged oxygen ions travel from the cathode (positive side of the fuel cell) to the anode (negative side of the fuel cell) instead of protons travelling vice versa (i.e., from the anode to the cathode), as is the case in all other types of fuel cells.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Oxygen gas is fed through the cathode, where it absorbs electrons to create oxygen ions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The oxygen ions then travel through the electrolyte to react with hydrogen gas at the anode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The reaction at the anode produces electricity and water as by-products.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Carbon dioxide may also be a by-product depending on the fuel, but the carbon emissions from a SOFC system are less than those from a fossil fuel combustion plant.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] SOFC systems can run on fuels other than pure hydrogen gas.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] However, since hydrogen is necessary for the reactions listed above, the fuel selected must contain hydrogen atoms.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] For the fuel cell to operate, the fuel must be converted into pure hydrogen gas.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] SOFCs are capable of internally reforming light hydrocarbons such as methane (natural gas), propane, and butane.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] These fuel cells are at an early stage of development.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Challenges exist in SOFC systems due to their high operating temperatures.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] One such challenge is the potential for carbon dust to build up on the anode, which slows down the internal reforming process.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Research to address this "carbon coking" issue at the University of Pennsylvania has shown that the use of copper-based cermet (heat-resistant materials made of ceramic and metal) can reduce coking and the loss of performance.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Another disadvantage of SOFC systems is the long start-up, making SOFCs less useful for mobile applications.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Despite these disadvantages, a high operating temperature provides an advantage by removing the need for a precious metal catalyst like platinum, thereby reducing cost.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Additionally, waste heat from SOFC systems may be captured and reused, increasing the theoretical overall efficiency to as high as 80–85%.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The high operating temperature is largely due to the physical properties of the YSZ electrolyte.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] As temperature decreases, so does the ionic conductivity of YSZ.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Therefore, to obtain the optimum performance of the fuel cell, a high operating temperature is required.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] According to their website, Ceres Power, a UK SOFC fuel cell manufacturer, has developed a method of reducing the operating temperature of their SOFC system to 500–600 degrees Celsius.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] They replaced the commonly used YSZ electrolyte with a CGO (cerium gadolinium oxide) electrolyte.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The lower operating temperature allows them to use stainless steel instead of ceramic as the cell substrate, which reduces cost and start-up time of the system.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Molten carbonate fuel cells (MCFCs) require a high operating temperature, 650 °C (1,200 °F), similar to SOFCs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] MCFCs use lithium potassium carbonate salt as an electrolyte, and this salt liquefies at high temperatures, allowing for the movement of charge within the cell – in this case, negative carbonate ions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Like SOFCs, MCFCs are capable of converting fossil fuel to a hydrogen-rich gas in the anode, eliminating the need to produce hydrogen externally.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The reforming process creates CO2 emissions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] MCFC-compatible fuels include natural gas, biogas and gas produced from coal.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The hydrogen in the gas reacts with carbonate ions from the electrolyte to produce water, carbon dioxide, electrons and small amounts of other chemicals.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The electrons travel through an external circuit, creating electricity, and return to the cathode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] There, oxygen from the air and carbon dioxide recycled from the anode react with the electrons to form carbonate ions that replenish the electrolyte, completing the circuit.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] As with SOFCs, MCFC disadvantages include slow start-up times because of their high operating temperature.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] This makes MCFC systems not suitable for mobile applications, and this technology will most likely be used for stationary fuel-cell purposes.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The main challenge of MCFC technology is the cells' short life span.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The high-temperature and carbonate electrolyte lead to corrosion of the anode and cathode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] These factors accelerate the degradation of MCFC components, decreasing the durability and cell life.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Researchers are addressing this problem by exploring corrosion-resistant materials for components as well as fuel cell designs that may increase cell life without decreasing performance.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] MCFCs hold several advantages over other fuel cell technologies, including their resistance to impurities.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] They are not prone to "carbon coking", which refers to carbon build-up on the anode that results in reduced performance by slowing down the internal fuel reforming process.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Therefore, carbon-rich fuels like gases made from coal are compatible with the system.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The United States Department of Energy claims that coal, itself, might even be a fuel option in the future, assuming the system can be made resistant to impurities such as sulfur and particulates that result from converting coal into hydrogen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] MCFCs also have relatively high efficiencies.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] They can reach a fuel-to-electricity efficiency of 50%, considerably higher than the 37–42% efficiency of a phosphoric acid fuel cell plant.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Efficiencies can be as high as 65% when the fuel cell is paired with a turbine, and 85% if heat is captured and used in a combined heat and power (CHP) system.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] FuelCell Energy, a Connecticut-based fuel cell manufacturer, develops and sells MCFC fuel cells.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The company says that their MCFC products range from 300 kW to 2.8 MW systems that achieve 47% electrical efficiency and can utilize CHP technology to obtain higher overall efficiencies.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] One product, the DFC-ERG, is combined with a gas turbine and, according to the company, it achieves an electrical efficiency of 65%.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The electric storage fuel cell is a conventional battery chargeable by electric power input, using the conventional electro-chemical effect.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] However, the battery further includes hydrogen (and oxygen) inputs for alternatively charging the battery chemically.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] A biofuel cell converts chemical energy from biological substances into electrical energy using biological catalysts, such as enzymes or microorganisms.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The process involves the oxidation of a fuel, like glucose, at the anode, releasing electrons and protons.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The electrons travel through an external circuit to generate electrical current, while at the cathode, oxygen is typically reduced to water or hydrogen peroxide, completing the circuit.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Applications include wastewater treatment and renewable energy production.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Conductive polymers may be used to improve electron transfer between enzymes and electrodes.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The integration of nanomaterials, such as carbon nanotubes and metal nanoparticles, are used to enhance the performance of BFCs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] These materials increase the surface area of electrodes and facilitate better electron transfer, resulting in higher power densities.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Three-dimensional porous structures and graphene-based materials, have been used to improve conductivity and stability, and hybrid biofuel cells that combine BFCs with supercapacitors or secondary batteries are being developed to provide stable and continuous energy output.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] BFCs are being explored as power sources for implantable devices like pacemakers and biosensors.to potentially eliminate the need for traditional batteries, and fiber-type EBFCs show potential in implantable applications.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The power density of BFCs, however, is generally lower than that of conventional energy sources, the stability of enzymes and microorganisms over extended periods is another concern, and scalability and commercial viability also pose hurdles.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The electrode at which oxidation (a loss of electrons) takes place.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] For fuel cells and other galvanic cells, the anode is the negative terminal; for electrolytic cells (where electrolysis occurs), the anode is the positive terminal.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] A chemical substance that increases the rate of a reaction without being consumed; after the reaction, it can potentially be recovered from the reaction mixture and is chemically unchanged.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The catalyst lowers the activation energy required, allowing the reaction to proceed more quickly or at a lower temperature.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] In a fuel cell, the catalyst facilitates the reaction of oxygen and hydrogen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] It is usually made of platinum powder very thinly coated onto carbon paper or cloth.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The catalyst is rough and porous so the maximum surface area of the platinum can be exposed to the hydrogen or oxygen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The platinum-coated side of the catalyst faces the membrane in the fuel cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The electrode at which reduction (a gain of electrons) occurs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] For fuel cells and other galvanic cells, the cathode is the positive terminal; for electrolytic cells (where electrolysis occurs), the cathode is the negative terminal.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] A substance that conducts charged ions from one electrode to the other in a fuel cell, battery, or electrolyzer.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Individual fuel cells connected in a series.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Fuel cells are stacked to increase voltage.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] something within or from which something else originates, develops, or takes form.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The separating layer in a fuel cell that acts as electrolyte (an ion-exchanger) as well as a barrier film separating the gases in the anode and cathode compartments of the fuel cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] A type of fuel cell that contains a molten carbonate electrolyte.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] ) are transported from the cathode to the anode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Operating temperatures are typically near 650 °C.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Protons (H+) are transported from the anode to the cathode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The operating temperature range is generally 160–220 °C.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] A fuel cell incorporating a solid polymer membrane used as its electrolyte.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The operating temperature range is generally 60–100 °C for Low Temperature Proton-exchange membrane fuel cell (LT-PEMFC).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] is transported from the cathode to the anode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Temperatures of operation are typically 800–1,000 °C.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] An act or the process by which a solid, liquid, or gaseous substance is homogeneously mixed with a liquid or sometimes a gas or solid.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] A homogeneous mixture formed by this process; especially : a single-phase liquid system.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The energy efficiency of a system or device that converts energy is measured by the ratio of the amount of useful energy put out by the system ("output energy") to the total amount of energy that is put in ("input energy") or by useful output energy as a percentage of the total input energy.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] In the case of fuel cells, useful output energy is measured in electrical energy produced by the system.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Input energy is the energy stored in the fuel.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Department of Energy, fuel cells are generally between 40 and 60% energy efficient.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] This is higher than some other systems for energy generation.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] For example, the internal combustion engine of a car can be about 43% energy efficient.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Steam power plants usually achieve efficiencies of 30-40% while combined cycle gas turbine and steam plants can achieve efficiencies above 60%.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] In combined heat and power (CHP) systems, the waste heat produced by the primary power cycle - whether fuel cell, nuclear fission or combustion - is captured and put to use, increasing the efficiency of the system to up to 85–90%.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The theoretical maximum efficiency of any type of power generation system is never reached in practice, and it does not consider other steps in power generation, such as production, transportation and storage of fuel and conversion of the electricity into mechanical power.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] However, this calculation allows the comparison of different types of power generation.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The theoretical maximum efficiency of a fuel cell approaches 100%, while the theoretical maximum efficiency of internal combustion engines is approximately 58%.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Values are given from 40% for acidic, 50% for molten carbonate, to 60% for alkaline, solid oxide and PEM fuel cells.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Fuel cells cannot store energy like a battery, except as hydrogen, but in some applications, such as stand-alone power plants based on discontinuous sources such as solar or wind power, they are combined with electrolyzers and storage systems to form an energy storage system.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] In addition, the overall efficiency (electricity to hydrogen and back to electricity) of such plants (known as *round-trip efficiency*), using pure hydrogen and pure oxygen can be "from 35 up to 50 percent", depending on gas density and other conditions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The electrolyzer/fuel cell system can store indefinite quantities of hydrogen, and is therefore suited for long-term storage.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Solid-oxide fuel cells produce heat from the recombination of the oxygen and hydrogen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The ceramic can run as hot as 800 °C (1,470 °F).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] This heat can be captured and used to heat water in a micro combined heat and power (m-CHP) application.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] When the heat is captured, total efficiency can reach 80–90% at the unit, but does not consider production and distribution losses.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] CHP units are being developed today for the European home market.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] In 2013 military organizations were evaluating fuel cells to determine if they could significantly reduce the battery weight carried by soldiers.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] In a fuel cell vehicle the tank-to-wheel efficiency is greater than 45% at low loads and shows average values of about 36% when a driving cycle like the NEDC (New European Driving Cycle) is used as test procedure.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] The comparable NEDC value for a Diesel vehicle is 22%.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] In 2008 Honda released a demonstration fuel cell electric vehicle (the Honda FCX Clarity) with fuel stack claiming a 60% tank-to-wheel efficiency.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] It is also important to take losses due to fuel production, transportation, and storage into account.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p01] Fuel cell vehicles running on compressed hydrogen may have a power-plant-to-wheel efficiency of 22% if the hydrogen is stored as high-pressure gas, and 17% if it is stored as liquid hydrogen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Stationary fuel cells are used for commercial, industrial and residential primary and backup power generation.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Fuel cells are very useful as power sources in remote locations, such as spacecraft, remote weather stations, large parks, communications centers, rural locations including research stations, and in certain military applications.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] A fuel cell system running on hydrogen can be compact and lightweight, and have no major moving parts.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Because fuel cells have no moving parts and do not involve combustion, in ideal conditions they can achieve up to 99.9999% reliability.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] This equates to less than one minute of downtime in a six-year period.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Since fuel cell electrolyzer systems do not store fuel in themselves, but rather rely on external storage units, they can be successfully applied in large-scale energy storage, rural areas being one example.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] There are many different types of stationary fuel cells so efficiencies vary, but most are between 40% and 60% energy efficient.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] However, when the fuel cell's waste heat is used to heat a building in a cogeneration system this efficiency can increase to 85%.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] This is significantly more efficient than traditional coal power plants, which are only about one third energy efficient.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Assuming production at scale, fuel cells could save 20–40% on energy costs when used in cogeneration systems.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Fuel Cells also produce 97% less nitrogen oxide emissions than conventional coal-fired power plants.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] One such pilot program is operating on Stuart Island in Washington State.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] There the Stuart Island Energy Initiative has built a complete, closed-loop system: Solar panels power an electrolyzer, which makes hydrogen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The hydrogen is stored in a 500-U.S.-gallon (1,900 L) tank at 200 pounds per square inch (1,400 kPa), and runs a ReliOn fuel cell to provide full electric back-up to the off-the-grid residence.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Another closed system loop was unveiled in late 2011 in Hempstead, NY.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Fuel cells can be used with low-quality gas from landfills or waste-water treatment plants to generate power and lower methane emissions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] A 2.8 MW fuel cell plant in California is said to be the largest of the type.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Small-scale (sub-5kWhr) fuel cells are being developed for use in residential off-grid deployment.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Combined heat and power (CHP) fuel cell systems, including micro combined heat and power (MicroCHP) systems are used to generate both electricity and heat for homes (see home fuel cell), office building and factories.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The system generates constant electric power (selling excess power back to the grid when it is not consumed), and at the same time produces hot air and water from the waste heat.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] As the result CHP systems have the potential to save primary energy as they can make use of waste heat which is generally rejected by thermal energy conversion systems.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] A typical capacity range of home fuel cell is 1–3 kWel, 4–8 kWth.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] CHP systems linked to absorption chillers use their waste heat for refrigeration.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The waste heat from fuel cells can be diverted during the summer directly into the ground providing further cooling while the waste heat during winter can be pumped directly into the building.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The University of Minnesota owns the patent rights to this type of system.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Co-generation systems can reach 85% efficiency (40–60% electric and the remainder as thermal).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Phosphoric-acid fuel cells (PAFC) comprise the largest segment of existing CHP products worldwide and can provide combined efficiencies close to 90%.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Molten carbonate (MCFC) and solid-oxide fuel cells (SOFC) are also used for combined heat and power generation and have electrical energy efficiencies around 60%.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Disadvantages of co-generation systems include slow ramping up and down rates, high cost and short lifetime.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Also their need to have a hot water storage tank to smooth out the thermal heat production was a serious disadvantage in the domestic market place where space in domestic properties is at a great premium.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Delta-ee consultants stated in 2013 that with 64% of global sales the fuel cell micro-combined heat and power passed the conventional systems in sales in 2012.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The Japanese ENE FARM project stated that 34.213 PEMFC and 2.224 SOFC were installed in the period 2012–2014, 30,000 units on LNG and 6,000 on LPG.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Four fuel cell electric vehicles have been introduced for commercial lease and sale: the Honda Clarity, Toyota Mirai, Hyundai ix35 FCEV, and the Hyundai Nexo.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] By year-end 2019, about 18,000 FCEVs had been leased or sold worldwide.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Fuel cell electric vehicles feature an average range of 505 km (314 mi) between refuelings and can be refueled in about 5 minutes.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Department of Energy's Fuel Cell Technology Program states that, as of 2011, fuel cells achieved 53–59% efficiency at one-quarter power and 42–53% vehicle efficiency at full power, and a durability of over 120,000 km (75,000 miles) with less than 10% degradation.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In 2015, Toyota introduced its first fuel cell vehicle, the Mirai, at a price of $57,000.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Hyundai introduced the limited production Hyundai ix35 FCEV under a lease agreement.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In 2016, Honda started leasing the Honda Clarity Fuel Cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In 2018, Hyundai introduced the Hyundai Nexo, replacing the Hyundai ix35 FCEV.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In 2020, Toyota introduced the second generation of its Mirai brand, improving fuel efficiency and expanding range compared to the original Sedan 2014 model.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The same year, Hyundai recalled all 1,600 Nexo vehicles sold in the US to that time due to a risk of fuel leaks and fire from a faulty "pressure relief device".
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Some commentators believe that hydrogen fuel cell cars will never become economically competitive with other technologies or that it will take decades for them to become profitable.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Elon Musk, CEO of battery-electric vehicle maker Tesla Motors, stated in 2015 that fuel cells for use in cars will never be commercially viable because of the inefficiency of producing, transporting and storing hydrogen and the flammability of the gas, among other reasons.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In 2012, Lux Research, Inc. issued a report that stated: "The dream of a hydrogen economy ... is no nearer".
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] It concluded that "Capital cost ... will limit adoption to a mere 5.9 GW" by 2030, providing "a nearly insurmountable barrier to adoption, except in niche applications".
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The analysis concluded that, by 2030, PEM stationary market will reach $1 billion, while the vehicle market, including forklifts, will reach a total of $2 billion.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Other analyses cite the lack of an extensive hydrogen infrastructure in the U.S. as an ongoing challenge to Fuel Cell Electric Vehicle commercialization.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In 2014, Joseph Romm, the author of *The Hype About Hydrogen* (2005; 2025), said that FCVs still had not overcome the high fueling cost, lack of fuel-delivery infrastructure, and pollution caused by producing hydrogen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] "It would take several miracles to overcome all of those problems simultaneously in the coming decades." He concluded that renewable energy cannot economically be used to make hydrogen for an FCV fleet "either now or in the future." Greentech Media's analyst reached similar conclusions in 2014.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In 2015, *CleanTechnica* listed some of the disadvantages of hydrogen fuel cell vehicles.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] A 2019 video by *Real Engineering* noted that, notwithstanding the introduction of vehicles that run on hydrogen, using hydrogen as a fuel for cars does not help to reduce carbon emissions from transportation.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The 95% of hydrogen still produced from fossil fuels releases carbon dioxide, and producing hydrogen from water is an energy-consuming process.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Storing hydrogen requires more energy either to cool it down to the liquid state or to put it into tanks under high pressure, and delivering the hydrogen to fueling stations requires more energy and may release more carbon.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The hydrogen needed to move a FCV a kilometer costs approximately 8 times as much as the electricity needed to move a BEV the same distance.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] A 2020 assessment concluded that hydrogen vehicles are still only 38% efficient, while battery EVs are 80% efficient.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] A 2023 study by the Centre for International Climate and Environmental Research (CICERO) estimated that leaked hydrogen has a global warming effect 11.6 times stronger than CO2.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] As of August 2011, there were about 100 fuel cell buses in service around the world.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Most of these were manufactured by UTC Power, Toyota, Ballard, Hydrogenics, and Proton Motor.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Fuel cell buses have from 39% to 141% higher fuel economy than diesel buses and natural gas buses.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] As of 2019, the NREL was evaluating several current and planned fuel cell bus projects in the U.S.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Train operators may use hydrogen fuel cells in trains in an effort to save the costs of installing overhead electrification and to maintain the range offered by diesel trains.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] They have encountered expenses, however, due to fuel cells in trains lasting only three years, maintenance of the hydrogen tank and the additional need for batteries as a power buffer.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In 2018, the first fuel cell-powered trains, the Alstom Coradia iLint multiple units, began running on the Buxtehude–Bremervörde–Bremerhaven–Cuxhaven line in Germany.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Hydrogen trains have also been introduced in Sweden and the UK.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In December 2020, Toyota and Hino Motors, together with Seven-Eleven (Japan), FamilyMart and Lawson announced that they have agreed to jointly consider introducing light-duty fuel cell electric trucks (light-duty FCETs).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Lawson started testing for low temperature delivery at the end of July 2021 in Tokyo, using a Hino Dutro in which the Toyota Mirai fuel cell is implemented.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] FamilyMart started testing in Okazaki city.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In August 2021, Toyota announced their plan to make fuel cell modules at its Kentucky auto-assembly plant for use in zero-emission big rigs and heavy-duty commercial vehicles.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] They plan to begin assembling the electrochemical devices in 2023.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In October 2021, Daimler Truck's fuel cell based truck received approval from German authorities for use on public roads.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] A fuel cell forklift (also called a fuel cell lift truck) is a fuel cell-powered industrial forklift truck used to lift and transport materials.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In 2013 there were over 4,000 fuel cell forklifts used in material handling in the US, of which 500 received funding from DOE (2012).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] As of 2024, approximately 50,000 hydrogen forklifts are in operation worldwide (the bulk of which are in the U.S.), as compared with 1.2 million battery electric forklifts that were purchased in 2021.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Most companies in Europe and the US do not use petroleum-powered forklifts, as these vehicles work indoors where emissions must be controlled and instead use electric forklifts.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Fuel cell-powered forklifts can be refueled in 3 minutes and they can be used in refrigerated warehouses, where their performance is not degraded by lower temperatures.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The FC units are often designed as drop-in replacements.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In 2005, a British manufacturer of hydrogen-powered fuel cells, Intelligent Energy (IE), produced the first working hydrogen-run motorcycle called the ENV (Emission Neutral Vehicle).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The motorcycle holds enough fuel to run for four hours, and to travel 160 km (100 miles) in an urban area, at a top speed of 80 km/h (50 mph).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In 2004 Honda developed a fuel cell motorcycle that utilized the Honda FC Stack.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Other examples of motorbikes and bicycles that use hydrogen fuel cells include the Taiwanese company APFCT's scooter using the fueling system from Italy's Acta SpA and the Suzuki Burgman scooter with an IE fuel cell that received EU Whole Vehicle Type Approval in 2011.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Suzuki Motor Corp. and IE have announced a joint venture to accelerate the commercialization of zero-emission vehicles.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In 2003, the world's first propeller-driven airplane to be powered entirely by a fuel cell was flown.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The fuel cell was a stack design that allowed the fuel cell to be integrated with the plane's aerodynamic surfaces.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Fuel cell-powered unmanned aerial vehicles (UAV) include a Horizon fuel cell UAV that set the record distance flown for a small UAV in 2007.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Boeing researchers and industry partners throughout Europe conducted experimental flight tests in February 2008 of a manned airplane powered only by a fuel cell and lightweight batteries.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The fuel cell demonstrator airplane, as it was called, used a proton-exchange membrane (PEM) fuel cell/lithium-ion battery hybrid system to power an electric motor, which was coupled to a conventional propeller.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In 2009, the Naval Research Laboratory's (NRL's) Ion Tiger utilized a hydrogen-powered fuel cell and flew for 23 hours and 17 minutes.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Fuel cells are also being tested and considered to provide auxiliary power in aircraft, replacing fossil fuel generators that were previously used to start the engines and power on board electrical needs, while reducing carbon emissions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In 2016 a Raptor E1 drone made a successful test flight using a fuel cell that was lighter than the lithium-ion battery it replaced.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The flight lasted 10 minutes at an altitude of 80 metres (260 ft), although the fuel cell reportedly had enough fuel to fly for two hours.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The fuel was contained in approximately 100 solid 1 square centimetre (0.16 sq in) pellets composed of a proprietary chemical within an unpressurized cartridge.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The pellets are physically robust and operate at temperatures as warm as 50 °C (122 °F).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Lockheed Martin Skunk Works Stalker is an electric UAV powered by solid oxide fuel cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The Hydra, a 22-person fuel cell boat operated from 1999 to 2001 on the Rhine river near Bonn, Germany, and was used as a ferry boat in Ghent, Belgium, during an electric boat conference in 2000.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] It was fully certified by the Germanischer Lloyd for passenger transport.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The Zemship, a small passenger ship, was produced in 2003 to 2013.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] It used a 100 kW Polymer Electrolyte Membrane Fuel Cells (PEMFC) with 7 lead gel batteries.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] With these systems, alongside 12 storage tanks, fuel cells provided an energy capacity of 560 V and 234 kWh.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Made in Hamburg, Germany, the FCS Alsterwasser, revealed in 2008, was one of the first passenger ships powered by fuel cells and could carry 100 passengers.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The hybrid fuel cell technology that powered this ship was produced by Proton Motor Fuel Cell GmbH.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In 2010, the MF Vågen was first produced, utilizing 12 kW fuel cells and 2- to 3-kilogram metal hydride hydrogen storage.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] It also utilizes 25 kWh lithium batteries and a 10 kW DC motor.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] It utilizes a diesel generator, batteries, photovoltaics, wind power, and fuel cells for energy.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Made in Bristol, a 12-passenger hybrid ferry, Hydrogenesis, has been in operation since 2012.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The SF-BREEZE is a two-motor boat that utilizes 41 × 120 kW fuel cells.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] With a type C storage tank, the pressurized vessel can maintain 1200 kg of LH2.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] These ships are still in operation today.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In Norway, the first ferry powered by fuel cells running on liquid hydrogen was scheduled for its first test drives in December 2022.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The Type 212 submarines of the German and Italian navies use fuel cells to remain submerged for weeks without the need to surface.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The U212A is a non-nuclear submarine developed by German naval shipyard Howaldtswerke Deutsche Werft.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The system consists of nine PEM fuel cells, providing between 30 kW and 50 kW each.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The ship is silent, giving it an advantage in the detection of other submarines.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Portable fuel cell systems are generally classified as weighing under 10 kg and providing power of less than 5 kW.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The potential market size for smaller fuel cells was estimated in 2002 at around $10 billion.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Within this market two groups have been identified.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The first is the microfuel cell market, in the 1-50 W range for power smaller electronic devices.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The second is the 1-5 kW range of generators for larger scale power generation (e.g. military outposts, remote oil fields).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Microfuel cells are primarily aimed at penetrating the market for phones and laptops.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Portable power systems that use fuel cells can be used in the leisure sector (i.e.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] RVs, cabins, marine), industry (i.e. power for remote locations including gas/oil wellsites, communication towers, security, weather stations), and the military.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] SFC Energy is a German manufacturer of direct methanol fuel cells for a variety of portable power systems.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Ensol Systems Inc. is an integrator of portable power systems, using the SFC Energy DMFC.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The key advantage of fuel cells in this market is the great power generation per weight.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] While fuel cells can be expensive, for remote locations that require dependable energy fuel cells hold great power.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] According to FuelCellsWorks, an industry group, at the end of 2019, 330 hydrogen refueling stations were open to the public worldwide.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] As of June 2020, there were 178 publicly available hydrogen stations in operation in Asia.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] There were at least 177 stations in Europe, and about half of these were in Germany.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] There were 44 publicly accessible stations in the US, 42 of which were located in California.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] A hydrogen fueling station costs between $1 million and $4 million to build.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] As of 2023, technological barriers to fuel cell adoption remain.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Fuel cells are primarily for material handling in warehouses, distribution centers, and manufacturing facilities.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] They are projected to be useful as an alternative to fossil fuels in a range applications.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] But applications have not often reached lower-income communities, though some attempts at inclusivity have been made, for example in accessibility.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In 2012, fuel cell industry revenues exceeded $1 billion market value worldwide, with Asian pacific countries shipping more than 3/4 of the fuel cell systems worldwide.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] There were 140,000 fuel cell stacks shipped globally in 2010, up from 11,000 shipments in 2007, and from 2011 to 2012 worldwide fuel cell shipments had an annual growth rate of 85%.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Tanaka Kikinzoku expanded its manufacturing facilities in 2011.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] Approximately 50% of fuel cell shipments in 2010 were stationary fuel cells, up from about a third in 2009, and the four dominant producers in the Fuel Cell Industry were the United States, Germany, Japan and South Korea.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] The Department of Energy Solid State Energy Conversion Alliance found that, as of January 2011, stationary fuel cells generated power at approximately $724 to $775 per kilowatt installed.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In 2011, Bloom Energy, a major fuel cell supplier, said that its fuel cells generated power at 9–11 cents per kilowatt-hour, including the price of fuel, maintenance, and hardware.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/fuel-cell-p02] In 2016, Samsung "decided to drop fuel cell-related business projects, as the outlook of the market isn't good".
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The **hydrogen economy** is a term for the role hydrogen as an energy carrier to complement electricity as part of a long-term option to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The aim is to reduce emissions where cheaper and more energy-efficient clean solutions are not available.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In this context, *hydrogen economy* encompasses the production of hydrogen and the use of hydrogen in ways that contribute to phasing-out fossil fuels and limiting climate change.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydrogen can be produced by several means.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Most hydrogen produced today is *gray hydrogen*, made from natural gas through steam methane reforming (SMR).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] This process accounted for 1.8% of global greenhouse gas emissions in 2021.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] *Low-carbon hydrogen*, which is made using SMR with carbon capture and storage (*blue hydrogen*), or through electrolysis of water using renewable power (*green hydrogen*), accounted for less than 1% of production.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Of the 100 million tonnes of hydrogen produced in 2021, 43% was used in oil refining and 57% in industry, principally in the manufacture of ammonia for fertilizers, and methanol.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] To limit global warming, it is generally envisaged that the future hydrogen economy replace gray hydrogen with low-carbon hydrogen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] As of 2024 it is unclear when enough low-carbon hydrogen could be produced to phase-out all the gray hydrogen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Other applications, such as light duty vehicles and heating in buildings, are no longer part of the future hydrogen economy, primarily for economic and environmental reasons.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydrogen is challenging to store, to transport in pipelines, and to use.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] It presents safety concerns since it is highly explosive, and it is inefficient compared to direct use of electricity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Since relatively small amounts of low-carbon hydrogen are available, climate benefits can be maximized by using it in harder-to-decarbonize applications.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] As of 2023 there are no real alternatives to hydrogen for several chemical processes in which it is currently used, such as ammonia production for fertilizer.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The cost of low- and zero-carbon hydrogen is likely to influence the degree to which it will be used in chemical feedstocks, long haul aviation and shipping, and long-term energy storage.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Production costs of low- and zero-carbon hydrogen are evolving.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Future costs may be influenced by carbon taxes, the geography and geopolitics of energy, energy prices, technology choices, and their raw material requirements.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Department of Energy's Hydrogen Hotshot Initiative seeks to reduce the cost of green hydrogen drop to $1 a kilogram by 2031, though the cost of electrolyzers rose 50% between 2021 and 2024.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The concept of a society that uses hydrogen as the primary means of energy storage was theorized by geneticist J.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Anticipating the exhaustion of Britain's coal reserves for power generation, Haldane proposed a network of wind turbines to produce hydrogen and oxygen for long-term energy storage through electrolysis, to help address renewable power's variable output.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The term "hydrogen economy" itself was coined by John Bockris during a talk he gave in 1970 at General Motors (GM) Technical Center.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Bockris viewed it as an economy in which hydrogen, underpinned by nuclear and solar power, would help address growing concern about fossil fuel depletion and environmental pollution, by serving as energy carrier for end-uses in which electrification was not suitable.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] A hydrogen economy was proposed by the University of Michigan to solve some of the negative effects of using hydrocarbon fuels where the carbon is released to the atmosphere (as carbon dioxide, carbon monoxide, unburnt hydrocarbons, etc.).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Modern interest in the hydrogen economy can generally be traced to a 1970 technical report by Lawrence W.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Jones of the University of Michigan, in which he echoed Bockris' dual rationale of addressing energy security and environmental challenges.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Unlike Haldane and Bockris, Jones only focused on nuclear power as the energy source for electrolysis, and principally on the use of hydrogen in transport, where he regarded aviation and heavy goods transport as the top priorities.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In 1974 International Energy Agency (IEA) and the International Association for Hydrogen Energy (IAHE) were established.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] These organizations had several initiatives including advocating for national strategies to increase interest and visibility of the hydrogen economy.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] A spike in attention for the *hydrogen economy* concept during the 2000s was repeatedly described as hype by some critics and proponents of alternative technologies, and investors lost money in the bubble.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Interest in the energy carrier resurged in the 2010s, notably with the forming of the Hydrogen Council in 2017.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Several manufacturers released hydrogen fuel cell cars commercially, and manufacturers such as Toyota, Hyundai, and industry groups in China planned to increase numbers of the cars into the hundreds of thousands over the next decade.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] However, the global scope for hydrogen's role in cars is shrinking relative to earlier expectations.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] By the end of 2022, 70,200 hydrogen vehicles had been sold worldwide, compared with 26 million plug-in electric vehicles.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Early 2020s takes on the hydrogen economy share earlier perspectives' emphasis on the complementarity of electricity and hydrogen, and the use of electrolysis as the mainstay of hydrogen production.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Since 2017, several countries and regions have released a **hydrogen strategy**, outlining their goals in developing hydrogen infrastructure and as a guide for private investment.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The International Renewable Energy Agency has proposed *national strategies* as the first pillar of policies to promote green hydrogen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In 2017 Japan published their strategy with a proposal to become the world's first "hydrogen society".
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Many provinces and cities in China have established hydrogen strategies.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The European Union strategy, adopted in 2021, outlines a plan to develop large scale infrastructure for hydrogen including electrolysers in collaboration with multiple trade organizations.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The US hydrogen strategy "presents a strategic framework for achieving large-scale production and use of hydrogen" over a 30 year period.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Analysis suggests that even nations reliant on exports of natural gas like Qatar could benefit from hydrogen strategies that leverage existing infrastructure, expertise, and markets.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] As of 2021, 28 governments had published hydrogen strategies.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] However the actual strategies proposed are not necessarily based on climate friendly green hydrogen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The majority of the strategies have been characterized by *scale first and clean later*, meaning they add regulations to enhance the viability of green hydrogen but do not mandate it use.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Economic analysis shows few national strategies can make their 2030 goals.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydrogen production globally was valued at over US$155 billion in 2022 and is expected to grow over 9% annually through 2030.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In 2021, 94 million tonnes (Mt) of molecular hydrogen (H2) was produced.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Of this total, approximately one sixth was as a by-product of petrochemical industry processes.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Most hydrogen comes from dedicated production facilities, over 99% of which is from fossil fuels, mainly via steam reforming of natural gas (70%) and coal gasification (30%, almost all of which in China).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Less than 1% of dedicated hydrogen production is low carbon: steam fossil fuel reforming with carbon capture and storage, green hydrogen produced using electrolysis, and hydrogen produced from biomass.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] CO2 emissions from 2021 production, at 915 MtCO2, amounted to 2.5% of energy-related CO2 emissions and 1.8% of global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Virtually all hydrogen produced for the current market is used in oil refining (40 MtH2 in 2021) and industry (54 MtH2).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In oil refining, hydrogen is used, in a process known as hydrocracking, to convert heavy petroleum sources into lighter fractions suitable for use as fuels.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Industrial uses mainly comprise ammonia production to make fertilizers (34 MtH2 in 2021), methanol production (15 MtH2) and the manufacture of direct reduced iron (5 MtH2).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydrogen gas is produced by several industrial methods.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Nearly all of the world's current supply of hydrogen is created from fossil fuels.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Most hydrogen is *gray hydrogen* made through steam methane reforming.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In this process, hydrogen is produced from a chemical reaction between steam and methane, the main component of natural gas.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Producing one tonne of hydrogen through this process emits 6.6–9.3 tonnes of carbon dioxide.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] When carbon capture and storage is used to remove a large fraction of these emissions, the product is known as *blue hydrogen*.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] As of 2023, less than 1% of dedicated hydrogen production is low-carbon, i.e. blue hydrogen, green hydrogen, and hydrogen produced from biomass.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Green methanol is a liquid fuel that is produced from combining carbon dioxide and hydrogen (CO2 + 3 H2 → CH3OH + H2O) under pressure and heat with catalysts.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] It is a way to reuse carbon capture for recycling.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Methanol can store hydrogen economically at standard outdoor temperatures and pressures, compared to liquid hydrogen and ammonia that need to use a lot of energy to stay cold in their liquid state.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In 2023 the Laura Maersk was the first container ship to run on methanol fuel.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Ethanol plants in the midwest are a good place for pure carbon capture to combine with hydrogen to make green methanol, with abundant wind and nuclear energy in Iowa, Minnesota, and Illinois.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Mixing methanol with ethanol could make methanol a safer fuel to use because methanol doesn't have a visible flame in the daylight and doesn't emit smoke, and ethanol has a visible light yellow flame.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Green hydrogen production of 70% efficiency and a 70% efficiency of methanol production from that would be a 49% energy conversion efficiency.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydrogen can be deployed as a fuel in two distinct ways: in fuel cells which produce electricity, and via combustion to generate heat.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] When hydrogen is consumed in fuel cells, the only emission at the point of use is water vapor.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Combustion of hydrogen can lead to the thermal formation of harmful nitrogen oxides emissions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In the context of limiting global warming, low-carbon hydrogen (particularly green hydrogen) is likely to play an important role in decarbonizing industry.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydrogen fuel can produce the intense heat required for industrial production of steel, cement, glass, and chemicals, thus contributing to the decarbonization of industry alongside other technologies, such as electric arc furnaces for steelmaking.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] However, it is likely to play a larger role in providing industrial feedstock for cleaner production of ammonia and organic chemicals.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] For example, in steelmaking, hydrogen could function as a clean energy carrier and also as a low-carbon catalyst replacing coal-derived coke.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Much of the interest in the hydrogen economy concept is focused on hydrogen vehicles, primarily forklifts, airport service vehicles, public transportation busses, cars and trucks.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Other applications are more speculative, including possible hydrogen planes.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydrogen vehicles produce significantly less local air pollution than conventional vehicles.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] By 2050, the energy requirement for transportation might be between 20% and 30% fulfilled by hydrogen and synthetic fuels.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydrogen used to decarbonize transportation is likely to find its largest applications in shipping, aviation and to a lesser extent heavy goods vehicles, through the use of hydrogen-derived synthetic fuels such as ammonia and methanol, and fuel cell technology.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydrogen has been used in fuel cell buses for many years.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] It is also used as a fuel for spacecraft propulsion.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In the International Energy Agency's 2022 Net Zero Emissions Scenario (NZE), hydrogen is forecast to account for 2% of rail energy demand in 2050, while 90% of rail travel is expected to be electrified by then (up from 45% today).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydrogen's role in rail would likely be focused on lines that prove difficult or costly to electrify.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The NZE foresees hydrogen meeting approximately 30% of heavy truck energy demand in 2050, mainly for long-distance heavy freight (with battery electric power accounting for around 60%).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Although hydrogen can be used in adapted internal combustion engines, fuel cells, being electrochemical, have an efficiency advantage over heat engines.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Fuel cells are more expensive to produce than common internal combustion engines but also require higher purity hydrogen fuel than internal combustion engines.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In the light road vehicle segment including passenger cars, by the end of 2022, 70,200 fuel cell electric vehicles had been sold worldwide, compared with 26 million plug-in electric vehicles.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] With the rapid rise of electric vehicles and associated battery technology and infrastructure, hydrogen's role in cars is minuscule.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Green hydrogen, from electrolysis of water, has the potential to address the variability of renewable energy output.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydrogen energy is a clean fuel that produces only water when used in fuel cells.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] While most hydrogen comes from natural gas, green hydrogen from renewables offers a zero-emission alternative.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Producing green hydrogen can both reduce the need for renewable power curtailment during periods of high renewables output and be stored long-term to provide for power generation during periods of low output.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] An alternative to gaseous hydrogen as an energy carrier is to bond it with nitrogen from the air to produce ammonia, which can be easily liquefied, transported, and used (directly or indirectly) as a clean and renewable fuel.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Among disadvantages of ammonia as an energy carrier are its high toxicity, energy efficiency of NH3 production from N2 and H2, and poisoning of PEM Fuel Cells by traces of non-decomposed NH3 after NH3 to N2 conversion.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Numerous industry groups (gas networks, gas boiler manufacturers) across the natural gas supply chain are promoting hydrogen combustion boilers for space and water heating, and hydrogen appliances for cooking, to reduce energy-related CO2 emissions from residential and commercial buildings.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The proposition is that current end-users of piped natural gas can await the conversion of and supply of hydrogen to existing natural gas grids, and then swap heating and cooking appliances, and that there is no need for consumers to do anything now.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Due to inefficiencies in hydrogen production, using blue hydrogen to replace natural gas for heating could require three times as much methane, while using green hydrogen would need two to three times as much electricity as heat pumps.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hybrid heat pumps, which combine the use of an electric heat pump with a hydrogen boiler, may play a role in residential heating in areas where upgrading networks to meet peak electrical demand would otherwise be costly.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The widespread use of hydrogen for heating buildings would entail higher energy system costs, higher heating costs and higher environmental impacts than the alternatives, although a niche role may be appropriate in specific contexts and geographies.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] If deployed, using hydrogen in buildings would drive up the cost of hydrogen for harder-to-decarbonize applications in industry and transport.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Synthetic Natural Gas (SNG) can be produced from low rank coal/lignite by using hydrogen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In hydrogen pipelines and steel storage vessels, hydrogen molecules are prone to react with metals, causing hydrogen embrittlement and leaks in the pipeline or storage vessel.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Since it is lighter than air, hydrogen does not easily accumulate to form a combustible gas mixture.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] However, even without ignition sources, high-pressure hydrogen leakage may cause spontaneous combustion and detonation.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydrogen is flammable when mixed even in small amounts with air.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Ignition can occur at a volumetric ratio of hydrogen to air as low as 4%.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In approximately 70% of hydrogen ignition accidents, the ignition source cannot be found, and it is widely believed by scholars that spontaneous ignition of hydrogen occurs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydrogen fire, while being extremely hot, is almost invisible, and thus can lead to accidental burns.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydrogen, like most gases, can cause asphyxiation in the absence of adequate ventilation.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] A hydrogen infrastructure is the infrastructure of points of hydrogen production, truck and pipeline transport, and hydrogen stations for the distribution and sale of hydrogen fuel, and thus a crucial prerequisite before a successful commercialization of fuel cell technology.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydrogen stations which are not situated near a hydrogen pipeline get supply via compressed hydrogen tube trailers, liquid hydrogen trailers, liquid hydrogen tank trucks or dedicated onsite production.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Pipelines are the cheapest way to move hydrogen over long distances but must be designed to withstand the leakage and steel embrittlement caused by the hydrogen molecule.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydrogen gas piping is routine in large oil-refineries, because hydrogen is used to hydrocrack fuels from crude oil.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The IEA recommends existing industrial ports be used for production and natural gas pipelines for transport, international co-operation and shipping.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] South Korea and Japan, which as of 2019 lacked international electrical interconnectors, were investing in the hydrogen economy.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In March 2020, the Fukushima Hydrogen Energy Research Field was opened in Japan, claiming to be the world's largest hydrogen production facility.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Much of the site is occupied by a solar array; power from the grid is also used for electrolysis of water to produce hydrogen fuel.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Several methods exist for storing hydrogen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] These include mechanical approaches such as using high pressures and low temperatures, or employing chemical compounds that release H2 upon demand.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] While large amounts of hydrogen are produced by various industries, it is mostly consumed at the site of production, notably for the synthesis of ammonia.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] For many years hydrogen has been stored as compressed gas or cryogenic liquid, and transported as such in cylinders, tubes, and cryogenic tanks for use in industry or as propellant in space programs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The overarching challenge is the very low boiling point of H2: it boils around 20.268 K (−252.882 °C or −423.188 °F).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Achieving such low temperatures requires expending significant energy.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Although molecular hydrogen has very high energy density on a mass basis, partly because of its low molecular weight, as a gas at ambient conditions it has very low energy density by volume.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] If it is to be used as fuel stored on board a vehicle, pure hydrogen gas must be stored in an energy-dense form to provide sufficient driving range.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Because hydrogen is the smallest molecule, it easily escapes from containers.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Its effective 100-year global warming potential (GWP100) is estimated to be 11.6 ± 2.8.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Xcel Energy is going to build two combined cycle power plants in the Midwest that can mix 30% hydrogen with the natural gas.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Intermountain Power Plant is being retrofitted to a natural gas/hydrogen power plant that can run on 30% hydrogen as well, and is scheduled to run on pure hydrogen by 2045.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] More widespread use of hydrogen in economies entails the need for investment and costs in its production, storage, distribution and use.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] These factors are incorporated into calculations of the levelized costs of hydrogen (LCOH).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The range of cost estimates for commercially available hydrogen production methods is broad.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] As of 2022, gray hydrogen is cheapest to produce without a tax on its CO2 emissions, followed by blue and green hydrogen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Blue hydrogen production costs are not anticipated to fall substantially by 2050, can be expected to fluctuate with natural gas prices and could face carbon taxes for uncaptured emissions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The cost of electrolysers fell by 60% from 2010 to 2022, but rose 50% between 2021 and 2024.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Oxford Institute for Energy Studies nevertheless projects that the cost of green hydrogen is likely to fall significantly towards 2030 and 2050, alongside the falling cost of renewable power generation.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] It is cheapest to produce green hydrogen with surplus renewable power that would otherwise be curtailed, which favors electrolyzers capable of responding to low and variable power levels.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] A 2022 Goldman Sachs analysis anticipates that globally green hydrogen will achieve cost parity with grey hydrogen by 2030, earlier if a global carbon tax is placed on gray hydrogen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In terms of cost per unit of energy, blue and gray hydrogen will always cost more than the fossil fuels used in its production, while green hydrogen will always cost more than the renewable electricity used to make it.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Subsidies for clean hydrogen production are much higher in the US and EU than in India.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The discovered price of green hydrogen in India is US$4.67 (INR 397) per kg as of June 2025.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The distribution of hydrogen for the purpose of transportation is being tested around the world, particularly in the US (California, Massachusetts), Canada, Japan, the EU (Portugal, Norway, the Netherlands, Denmark, Germany), and Iceland.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Natural gas vehicles can also be converted to run on hydrogen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Also, fuel cell micro-CHP plants can be found in Japan and across the European Union.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Such units can operate on hydrogen, or other fuels as natural gas or LPG.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Under the ene.field and PACE projects — both co-funded by the Fuel Cells and Hydrogen Joint Undertaking (FCH JU) — a total of approximately 3,646 fuel cell micro-CHP units were installed across the European Union and the UK.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Western Australia's Department of Planning and Infrastructure operated three Daimler Chrysler Citaro fuel cell buses as part of its Sustainable Transport Energy for Perth Fuel Cells Bus Trial in Perth from 2004 to 2007.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] By November 2020 the Australian Renewable Energy Agency (ARENA) had invested $55 million in 28 hydrogen projects, from early stage research and development to early stage trials and deployments.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The agency's stated goal is to produce hydrogen by electrolysis for $2 per kilogram, announced by Minister for Energy and Emissions Angus Taylor in a 2021 Low Emissions Technology Statement.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In October 2021, Queensland Premier Annastacia Palaszczuk and private investor Andrew Forrest announced that Queensland would be home to the world's largest hydrogen plant.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In November 2024, the South Australian Government's plan to spend A$593 million on a 200MW hydrogen energy plant near Whyalla was granted federal approval under the EPBC Act.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Construction was scheduled to start in 2025, with completion and commissioning happening in 2026.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In early 2022, China released the *Medium- and Long-Term Plan for the Development of the Hydrogen Energy Industry (2021–2035)*, outlining new development targets for the hydrogen sector over the subsequent 15 years .
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In November 2024, the *Energy Law of the People's Republic of China* was promulgated; effective January 1, 2025, this legislation officially conferred "energy" status upon hydrogen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] By 2026, China's total annual hydrogen production is projected to reach between 38 million and 40 million tons, accounting for 30% to 35% of the global total.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] This output is expected to comprise approximately 60% fossil-fuel-based hydrogen ("gray hydrogen"), 25% industrial by-product hydrogen ("blue hydrogen" or "quasi-blue hydrogen"), and 15% water-electrolysis-based hydrogen ("green hydrogen").
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Notably, the production capacity for renewable-energy-based hydrogen (green hydrogen) is set to officially surpass 1 million tons per year.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Regarding electrolyzer technology, China's production capacity for electrolyzers is expected to exceed 70% of the global total.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The hydrogen output of single alkaline (ALK) electrolyzer units is projected to increase to 5,000 Nm³/h, while Proton Exchange Membrane (PEM) and Anion Exchange Membrane (AEM) technologies are also expected to achieve large-scale commercial shipment volumes.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In the realm of storage and transportation, infrastructure is expected to evolve into an interconnected network.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In 2026, China is set to officially launch "Comprehensive Hydrogen Energy Application Pilot Programs," with a specific focus on establishing hydrogen-dedicated highways.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Provinces and municipalities—including Guangdong, Shandong, and the Beijing-Tianjin-Hebei region—have already taken the lead in implementing policies that grant hydrogen-powered vehicles free or discounted access to expressways.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Additionally, ammonia (NH3)-based hydrogen storage solutions are expected to find practical application across storage, transportation, and automotive sectors.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] A million-cubic-meter-scale salt cavern hydrogen storage demonstration project officially commenced operations in Pingdingshan, Henan Province, in April 2026 .
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Application Sector: Shifting from transportation to the "main battlefield" of industry.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Over 600 hydrogen refueling stations have been constructed; fuel cell stack lifetimes have surpassed the 25,000 to 30,000-hour mark; and high-power (260 kW+) fuel cell systems have entered mass production.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] By 2026, the cost of high-power stacks (exceeding 200 kW) had declined by approximately 40% compared to two years prior.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydrogen-powered heavy-duty trucks are transitioning from pilot projects to large-scale commercial operations, with individual fleet sizes now exceeding 1,200 vehicles.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Liquid hydrogen heavy-duty trucks can easily achieve driving ranges exceeding 1,000 kilometers and have entered small-scale mass production.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] These hydrogen heavy trucks cover a diverse range of applications—including short-haul shuttles for mines and steel mills, port logistics, and long-distance inter-provincial coal transport—with a cumulative deployment reaching 50,000 units.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] As of April 2026, China’s cumulative deployment of hydrogen-powered mining trucks exceeded 1,200 units.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Wide-body dump trucks (70–100-ton class) account for approximately 70% of this total, followed by ultra-heavy-duty rigid mining trucks (over 200-ton class) at about 20%, and emerging technology models (liquid hydrogen/ammonia-hydrogen) at roughly 10%.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] These vehicles are concentrated in the regions of Inner Mongolia, Xinjiang, Ningxia, and Shanxi, where they have been operating for over three years under extremely harsh environmental conditions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] With the direct supply cost of green hydrogen dropping to around 15 RMB/kg, the Total Cost of Ownership (TCO) for hydrogen mining trucks operating under continuous 24-hour duty cycles has become nearly comparable to that of diesel-powered vehicles.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In 2026, China’s hydrogen mining trucks were successfully exported to major mining conglomerates in Australia’s Pilbara region (350+ units), Southeast Asia (Indonesia: 200+ units), and South America (Chile and Peru: 120+ units).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydrogen Ports: Four major hydrogen port clusters have taken shape, centered around the ports of Qingdao, Ningbo-Zhoushan, Tianjin, and Shenzhen Yantian.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The total number of hydrogen-enabled ports nationwide now exceeds 20.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Within these ports, the fleet of hydrogen-powered heavy-duty trucks and container trucks stands at approximately 5,000 to 8,000 vehicles.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydrogen-powered rail-mounted gantry cranes and automated terminal equipment have been deployed for routine operations, while the self-sufficiency rate for green hydrogen supply within these ports has reached approximately 35%.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Furthermore, high-power hydrogen fuel cell tugboats have commenced operations in the Pearl River Delta and Yangtze River Delta regions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] By 2026, the national fleet of hydrogen-powered public buses is projected to number between 12,000 and 14,000 vehicles.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] These buses are primarily concentrated in regions with access to low-cost green hydrogen sources—such as Beijing, Zhangjiakou, Zhengzhou, and certain extreme-cold climate zones.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Consequently, other cities lacking access to affordable local hydrogen supplies have also begun adjusting their respective local policies.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Green Chemicals: The primary focus of hydrogen application is shifting from the transportation sector toward industrial decarbonization.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Million-ton-scale, near-zero-carbon steel production lines have achieved stable operation, marking the first instance where hydrogen has successfully replaced traditional coke as a reducing agent.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Additionally, a project in Ningxia—integrating a 150,000-ton-per-year green hydrogen facility with coal chemical production—has officially commenced operations.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Projects for the production of green ammonia and green alcohols (specifically green methanol) are coming online in rapid succession, directly addressing the rigid decarbonization demands of the shipping and refining industries.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] By 2026, hydrogen-powered trains and distributed hydrogen power generation stations are no longer considered novelties; indeed, cutting-edge explorations have even emerged at the intersection of hydrogen technology, quantum computing, and embodied AI.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] EU Member States which have a relatively large natural gas pipeline system already in place include Italy, Belgium, Germany, France, and the Netherlands.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In 2020, The EU launched its European Clean Hydrogen Alliance (ECHA).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Green hydrogen has become more common in France.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] A €150 million Green Hydrogen Plan was established in 2019, and it calls for building the infrastructure necessary to create, store, and distribute hydrogen as well as using the fuel to power local transportation systems like buses and trains.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Corridor H2, a similar initiative, will create a network of hydrogen distribution facilities in Occitania along the route between the Mediterranean and the North Sea.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The Corridor H2 project will get a €40 million loan from the EIB.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] German car manufacturer BMW has been working with hydrogen for years..
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Iceland has committed to becoming the world's first hydrogen economy by the year 2050.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] As of 2024-2026, Iceland continues to import nearly all the petroleum products necessary to power its transportation and fishing fleet.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Iceland has large geothermal resources, making the transition to a hydrogen economy easier.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Iceland already converts its surplus electricity into exportable goods and hydrocarbon replacements.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In 2002, it produced 2,000 tons of hydrogen gas by electrolysis, primarily for the production of ammonia (NH3) for fertilizer.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Ammonia is produced, transported, and used throughout the world, and 90% of the cost of ammonia is the cost of the energy to produce it.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Neither industry directly replaces hydrocarbons.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Reykjavík, Iceland, had a small pilot fleet of city buses running on compressed hydrogen, and research on powering the nation's fishing fleet with hydrogen is under way (for example by companies as Icelandic New Energy).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] For more practical purposes, Iceland might process imported oil with hydrogen to extend it, rather than to replace it altogether.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The Reykjavík buses are part of a larger program, HyFLEET:CUTE, operating hydrogen fueled buses in eight European cities.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] HyFLEET:CUTE buses were also operated in Beijing, China and Perth, Australia (see below).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] A pilot project demonstrating a hydrogen economy is operational on the Norwegian island of Utsira.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The installation combines wind power and hydrogen power.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In periods when there is surplus wind energy, the excess power is used for generating hydrogen by electrolysis.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The hydrogen is stored, and is available for power generation in periods when there is little wind.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The discovered price of green hydrogen in India is US$3.9 (INR 328) per kg as of July 2025.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The discovered price of green ammonia in India is US$641 (INR 55,750) per tonne as of July 2025.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] India is said to adopt hydrogen and H-CNG, due to several reasons, amongst which the fact that a national rollout of natural gas networks is already taking place and natural gas is already a major vehicle fuel.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In addition, India suffers from extreme air pollution in urban areas.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] According to some estimates, nearly 80% of India's hydrogen is projected to be green, driven by cost declines and new production technologies.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Currently however, hydrogen energy is just at the Research, Development and Demonstration (RD&D) stage.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] As a result, the number of hydrogen stations may still be low, although much more are expected to be introduced soon.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] It planning open first hydrogen publication stations, The Ministry of Climate and Environment (MKiŚ) will soon schan competitions for 2-3 hydrogen refueling stations, Polish Deputy Minister in this ministry Krzysztof Bolesta.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Saudi Arabia as a part of the NEOM project, is looking to produce roughly 1.2 million tonnes of green ammonia a year, beginning production in 2025.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In Cairo, Egypt, Saudi real estate funding skyscraper project powered by hydrogen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The Ulsan Green Hydrogen Town is a hydrogen city project being developed in Ulsan.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] As of October 2024, 188 km of underground pipelines have been laid to connect hydrogen produced as a byproduct from petrochemical complexes to the city center.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The Turkish Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources and the United Nations Industrial Development Organization created the International Centre for Hydrogen Energy Technologies (UNIDO-ICHET) in Istanbul in 2004 and it ran to 2012.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In 2023 the ministry published a Hydrogen Technologies Strategy and Roadmap.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The UK started a fuel cell pilot program in January 2004, the program ran two Fuel cell buses on route 25 in London until December 2005, and switched to route RV1 until January 2007.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The Hydrogen Expedition is currently working to create a hydrogen fuel cell-powered ship and using it to circumnavigate the globe, as a way to demonstrate the capability of hydrogen fuel cells.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In 2009, Dr Graham Cooley was appointed CEO of ITM Power PLC, a manufacturer of electrolysers for green hydrogen production.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Cooley raised almost £500 million for ITM and in 2021 opened the world’s largest electrolyser manufacturing facility in Sheffield.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Cooley also served as a member of the UK Government’s Hydrogen Advisory Council.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In August 2021 the UK Government claimed it was the first to have a Hydrogen Strategy and produced a document.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Several domestic U.S. automobile companies have developed vehicles using hydrogen, such as GM and Toyota.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] However, as of February 2020, infrastructure for hydrogen was underdeveloped except in some parts of California.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The United States have their own hydrogen policy.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] A joint venture between NREL and Xcel Energy is combining wind power and hydrogen power in the same way in Colorado.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydro in Newfoundland and Labrador are converting the current wind-diesel Power System on the remote island of Ramea into a Wind-Hydrogen Hybrid Power Systems facility.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Five pump station hubs being delivered to heavy-duty H2 trucks in Texas.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Hydrogen City built Green by Hydrogen International (GHI), to planning open in 2026.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] In 2006, Florida’s infrastructure project was commissioned.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] First opened Orlando as public bus transportation, Ford Motor Company announced putting a fleet of hydrogen-fueled Ford E-450.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Liquidated hydrogen mobile system was constructed at Titusville.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] An FPL’s pilot clean hydrogen facility operated in Okeechobee County.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] A similar pilot project on Stuart Island uses solar power, instead of wind power, to generate electricity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] When excess electricity is available after the batteries are fully charged, hydrogen is generated by electrolysis and stored for later production of electricity by fuel cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] The US also have a large natural gas pipeline system already in place.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Việt Nam Energy Association have included green hydrogenation support.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/hydrogen-fuel] Australian clean energy company Pure Hydrogen Corporation Limited announced on July 22 that it has signed an MoU with Vietnam public transportation.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/membrane-electrode-assembly] A **membrane electrode assembly** (**MEA**) is an assembled stack of proton-exchange membranes (PEM) or alkali anion exchange membrane (AAEM), catalyst and flat plate electrode used in fuel cells and electrolyzers.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/membrane-electrode-assembly] The PEM is sandwiched between two electrodes which have the catalyst embedded in them.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/membrane-electrode-assembly] The electrodes are electrically insulated from each other by the PEM.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/membrane-electrode-assembly] These two electrodes make up the anode and cathode respectively.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/membrane-electrode-assembly] The PEM is typically a fluoropolymer (PFSA) proton permeable electrical insulator barrier.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/membrane-electrode-assembly] Hydrocarbon variants are currently being developed and are expected to succeed fluoropolymers.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/membrane-electrode-assembly] This barrier allows the transport of the protons from the anode to the cathode through the membrane but forces the electrons to travel around a conductive path to the cathode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/membrane-electrode-assembly] The most commonly used Nafion PEMs are Nafion XL, 112, 115, 117, and 1110.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/membrane-electrode-assembly] The electrodes are heat pressed onto the PEM.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/membrane-electrode-assembly] Commonly used materials for these electrodes are carbon cloth or carbon fiber papers.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/membrane-electrode-assembly] NuVant produces a carbon cloth called ELAT which maximizes gas transport to the PEM as well as moves water vapor away from the PEM.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/membrane-electrode-assembly] Imbedding ELAT with noble metal catalyst allows this carbon cloth to also act as the electrode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/membrane-electrode-assembly] Many other different methods and procedures also exist for the production of MEAs which are quite similar between fuel cells and electrolyzers.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/membrane-electrode-assembly] Platinum is one of the most commonly used catalysts, however other platinum group metals are also used.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/membrane-electrode-assembly] Ruthenium and platinum are often used together, if carbon monoxide (CO) is a product of the electro-chemical reaction as CO poisons the PEM and impacts the efficiency of the fuel cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/membrane-electrode-assembly] Due to the high cost of these and other similar materials, research is being undertaken to develop catalysts that use lower cost materials as the high costs are still a hindering factor in the widespread economical acceptance of fuel cell technology.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/membrane-electrode-assembly] Current service life is 7,300 hours under cycling conditions, while at the same time reducing platinum group metal loading to 0.2 mg/cm2.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/membrane-electrode-assembly] At this time most companies manufacturing MEAs specialize solely in high volume production, such as W.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/membrane-electrode-assembly] Gore & Associates, Johnson Matthey, and 3M.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/membrane-electrode-assembly] However, there are other companies which produce MEAs, allowing different shapes, catalysts or membranes to be evaluated as well, which include Fuel Cell Store, FuelCellsEtc, and many others.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] PEMFCs are built out of membrane electrode assemblies (MEA) which include the electrodes, electrolyte, catalyst, and gas diffusion layers.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] An ink of catalyst, carbon, and electrode are sprayed or painted onto the solid electrolyte and carbon paper is hot pressed on either side to protect the inside of the cell and also act as electrodes.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The pivotal part of the cell is the triple phase boundary (TPB) where the electrolyte, catalyst, and reactants mix and thus where the cell reactions actually occur.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Importantly, the membrane must not be electrically conductive so the half reactions do not mix.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Operating temperatures above 100 °C are desired so the water byproduct becomes steam and water management becomes less critical in cell design.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] A proton exchange membrane fuel cell transforms the chemical energy liberated during the electrochemical reaction of hydrogen and oxygen to electrical energy, as opposed to the direct combustion of hydrogen and oxygen gases to produce thermal energy.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] A stream of hydrogen is delivered to the anode side of the MEA.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] At the anode side it is catalytically split into protons and electrons.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The newly formed protons permeate through the polymer electrolyte membrane to the cathode side.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The electrons travel along an external load circuit to the cathode side of the MEA, thus creating the current output of the fuel cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Meanwhile, a stream of oxygen is delivered to the cathode side of the MEA.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] At the cathode side oxygen molecules react with the protons permeating through the polymer electrolyte membrane and the electrons arriving through the external circuit to form water molecules.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The reversible reaction is expressed in the equation and shows the reincorporation of the hydrogen protons and electrons together with the oxygen molecule and the formation of one water molecule.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The potentials in each case are given with respect to the standard hydrogen electrode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] To function, the membrane must conduct hydrogen ions (protons) but not electrons as this would in effect "short circuit" the fuel cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The membrane must also not allow either gas to pass to the other side of the cell, a problem known as **gas crossover**.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Finally, the membrane must be resistant to the reducing environment at the cathode as well as the harsh oxidative environment at the anode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Splitting of the hydrogen molecule is relatively easy by using a platinum catalyst.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Unfortunately however, splitting the oxygen molecule is more difficult, and this causes significant electric losses.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] An appropriate catalyst material for this process has not been discovered, and platinum is the best option.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] PEMFCs have a thin, polymeric membrane as the electrolyte.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] This membrane is located in between the anode and cathode catalyst layers and allows the passage of protons to pass to the cathode while restricting the passage of electrons.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The better the connection of the polymeric membrane to the catalyst layer, the lower the interface resistance.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Compared to liquid electrolytes, a polymeric membrane has a much lower chance of leakage [2].
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The membrane is commonly made of materials such as perfluorosulfonic acid (PFSA, sold commercially as Nafion and Aquivion), which minimize gas crossover and short circuiting of the fuel cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] A disadvantage of fluor containing polymers is the fact that during production (and disposal) PFAS products are formed.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] PFAS, the so-called forever chemicals, are highly toxic.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Newer polymers such as the recently patented SPX3 (POLYMERS COMPRISING SULFONATED 2,6-DIPHENYL-1,4-PHENYLENE OXIDE REPEATING UNITS -US 11434329 B2) are fluor free and therefore do not carry the PFAS risk.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Under extreme sub-freezing conditions, the water produced by fuel cells can freeze in porous layers and flow channels.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] This freezing water can block gas and fuel transport as well as cover catalyst reaction sites, resulting in a loss of output power and a start-up failure of the fuel cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] However, the low operating temperature of a PEM fuel cell allows it to reach a suitable temperature with less heating compared to other types of fuel cells.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] With this approach, PEM fuel cells have been shown to be capable of cold start processes from −20°C.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] PEM fuel cells have been shown to be capable of high power densities up to 39.7 kW/kg, compared to 2.5 kW/kg for solid oxide fuel cells.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Due to this high power density, much research is being done on potential applications in transportation as well as wearable technology.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Both cases will cause damage to stability and power output.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Water management is a very difficult subject in PEM systems, primarily because water in the membrane is attracted toward the cathode of the cell through polarization.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] A wide variety of solutions for managing the water exist including integration of an electroosmotic pump.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Another innovative method to resolve the water recirculation problem is the 3D fine mesh flow field design used in the Toyota Mirai, 2014.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Conventional design of FC stack recirculates water from the air outlet to the air inlet through a humidifier with a straight channel and porous metal flow fields[54].The flow field is a structure made up of a rib and channels.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] However, the rib partially covers the gas diffusion layer (GDL) and the resultant gas-transport distance is longer than the inter-channel distance.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Furthermore, the contact pressure between the GDL and the rib also compresses the GDL, making its thickness non-uniform across the rib and channel[55].
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The large width and non-uniform thickness of the rib will increase potential for water vapor to accumulate and the oxygen will be compromised.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] As a result, oxygen will be impeded to diffuse into catalyst layer, leading to nonuniform power generation in the FC.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] This new design enabled the first FC stack functions without a humidifying system meanwhile overcoming water recirculation issues and achieving high power output stability[54].
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The 3D micro lattice allows more pathways for gas flow; therefore, it promotes airflow toward membrane electrode and gas diffusion layer assembly (MEGA) and promotes O2 diffusion to the catalyst layer.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Unlike conventional flow fields, the 3D micro-lattices in the complex field, which act as baffles and induce frequent micro-scale interfacial flux between the GDL and flow-fields[53].
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Due to this repeating micro-scale convective flow, oxygen transport to catalyst layer (CL) and liquid water removal from GDL is significantly enhanced.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The generated water is quickly drawn out through the flow field, preventing accumulation within the pores.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] As a result, the power generation from this flow field is uniform across the cross-section and self-humidification is enabled.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The platinum catalyst on the membrane is easily poisoned by carbon monoxide, which is often present in product gases formed by methane reforming (no more than one part per million is usually acceptable).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] This generally necessitates the use of the water gas shift reaction to eliminate CO from product gases and form more hydrogen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Additionally, the membrane is sensitive to the presences of metal ions, which may impair proton conduction mechanisms and can be introduced by corrosion of metallic bipolar plates, metallic components in the fuel cell system or from contaminants in the fuel/oxidant.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] PEM systems that use reformed methanol were proposed, as in Daimler Chrysler Necar 5; reforming methanol, i.e. making it react to obtain hydrogen, is however a very complicated process, that also requires purification from the carbon monoxide the reaction produces.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] A platinum-ruthenium catalyst is necessary as some carbon monoxide will unavoidably reach the membrane.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The level should not exceed 10 parts per million.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Furthermore, the start-up times of such a reformer reactor are of about half an hour.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Alternatively, methanol, and some other biofuels can be fed to a PEM fuel cell directly without being reformed, thus making a direct methanol fuel cell (DMFC).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] These devices operate with limited success.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The most commonly used membrane is Nafion by Chemours, which relies on liquid water humidification of the membrane to transport protons.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] This implies that it is not feasible to use temperatures above 80 to 90 °C, since the membrane would dry.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] PBI can be doped with phosphoric or sulfuric acid and the conductivity scales with amount of doping and temperature.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] At high temperatures, it is difficult to keep Nafion hydrated, but this acid doped material does not use water as a medium for proton conduction.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] It also exhibits better mechanical properties, higher strength, than Nafion and is cheaper.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] However, acid leaching is a considerable issue and processing, mixing with catalyst to form ink, has proved tricky.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Aromatic polymers, such as PEEK, are far cheaper than Teflon (PTFE and backbone of Nafion) and their polar character leads to hydration that is less temperature dependent than Nafion.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] However, PEEK is far less ionically conductive than Nafion and thus is a less favorable electrolyte choice.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Recently, protic ionic liquids and protic organic ionic plastic crystals have been shown as promising alternative electrolyte materials for high temperature (100–200 °C) PEMFCs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] An electrode typically consists of carbon support, Pt particles, Nafion ionomer, and/or Teflon binder.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The carbon support functions as an electrical conductor; the Pt particles are reaction sites; the ionomer provides paths for proton conduction, and the Teflon binder increases the hydrophobicity of the electrode to minimize potential flooding.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] These properties are typically realized by porous composites of polymer electrolyte binder (ionomer) and catalyst nanoparticles supported on carbon particles.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Typically platinum is used as the catalyst for the electrochemical reactions at the anode and cathode, while nanoparticles realize high surface to weight ratios (as further described below) reducing the amount of the costly platinum.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The polymer electrolyte binder provides the ionic conductivity, while the carbon support of the catalyst improves the electric conductivity and enables low platinum metal loading.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The electric conductivity in the composite electrodes is typically more than 40 times higher as the proton conductivity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The GDL electrically connects the catalyst and current collector.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] It must be porous, electrically conductive, and thin.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The reactants must be able to reach the catalyst, but conductivity and porosity can act as opposing forces.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Optimally, the GDL should be composed of about one third Nafion or 15% PTFE.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The carbon particles used in the GDL can be larger than those employed in the catalyst because surface area is not the most important variable in this layer.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] GDL should be around 15–35 μm thick to balance needed porosity with mechanical strength.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Often, an intermediate porous layer is added between the GDL and catalyst layer to ease the transitions between the large pores in the GDL and small porosity in the catalyst layer.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Since a primary function of the GDL is to help remove water, a product, flooding can occur when water effectively blocks the GDL.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] This limits the reactants ability to access the catalyst and significantly decreases performance.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Teflon can be coated onto the GDL to limit the possibility of flooding.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Several microscopic variables are analyzed in the GDLS such as: porosity, tortuosity and permeability.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] These variables have incidence over the behavior of the fuel cells.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The maximal theoretical efficiency applying the Gibbs free energy equation ΔG = −237.13 kJ/mol and using the heating value of Hydrogen (ΔH = −285.84 kJ/mol) is 83% at 298 K.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The practical efficiency of a PEMs is in the range of 50–60% .
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The external electrodes, often referred to as bipolar plates or backplates, serve to distribute fuel and oxygen uniformly to the catalysts, to remove water, to collect and transmit electric current.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Thus, they need to be in close contact with the catalyst.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Because the plates are in contact with both PEM and catalyst layers, the backplate needs to be structurally tough and leakage-resistant in case of structural failure due to fuel cell vibration and temperature cycling.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] As fuel cells operate in wide ranges of temperatures and in highly reductive/oxidative environments, plates must have high surface tolerances over the wide ranges of temperatures and should be chemically stable.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Since the backplate accounts for more than three-quarters of the fuel cell mass, the material must also be lightweight to maximize the energy density.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Materials that fulfill all of these requirements are often very expensive.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Gold has been shown to fulfill these criteria well, but is only used for small production volumes due to its high cost.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Titanium nitride (TiN) is a cheaper material that is used in fuel cell backplates due to its high chemical stability, electrical conductivity, and corrosion resistance.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] However, defects in the TiN coating can easily lead to corrosion of the underlying material, most commonly steel.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] To perform their main function of distributing gas and fuel, these plates often have straight, parallel channels across its surface.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] However, this simple approach has led to issues such as uneven pressure distribution, water droplets blocking gas flow, and output power oscillations.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Innovative approaches, such as nature-inspired fractal models and computer simulations are being explored to optimize the function of these bipolar plates.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Metal-organic frameworks (MOFs) are a relatively new class of porous, highly crystalline materials that consist of metal nodes connected by organic linkers.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Due to the simplicity of manipulating or substituting the metal centers and ligands, there are a virtually limitless number of possible combinations, which is attractive from a design standpoint.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] MOFs exhibit many unique properties due to their tunable pore sizes, thermal stability, high volume capacities, large surface areas, and desirable electrochemical characteristics.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Among their many diverse uses, MOFs are promising candidates for clean energy applications such as hydrogen storage, gas separations, supercapacitors, Li-ion batteries, solar cells, and fuel cells.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Within the field of fuel cell research, MOFs are being studied as potential electrolyte materials and electrode catalysts that could someday replace traditional polymer membranes and Pt catalysts, respectively.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] As electrolyte materials, the inclusion of MOFs seems at first counter-intuitive.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Fuel cell membranes generally have low porosity to prevent fuel crossover and loss of voltage between the anode and cathode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Additionally, membranes tend to have low crystallinity because the transport of ions is more favorable in disordered materials.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] On the other hand, pores can be filled with additional ion carriers that ultimately enhance the ionic conductivity of the system and high crystallinity makes the design process less complex.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] While polymeric materials are currently the preferred choice of proton-conducting membrane, they require humidification for adequate performance and can sometimes physically degrade due to hydrations effects, thereby causing losses of efficiency.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] As mentioned, Nafion is also limited by a dehydration temperature of < 100 °C, which can lead to slower reaction kinetics, poor cost efficiency, and CO poisoning of Pt electrode catalysts.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Conversely, MOFs have shown encouraging proton conductivities in both low and high temperature regimes as well as over a wide range of humidity conditions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Below 100 °C and under hydration, the presence of hydrogen bonding and solvent water molecules aid in proton transport, whereas anhydrous conditions are suitable for temperatures above 100 °C.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] MOFs also have the distinct advantage of exhibiting proton conductivity by the framework itself in addition to the inclusion of charge carries (i.e., water, acids, etc.) into their pores.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] A low temperature example is work by Kitagawa, et al. who used a two-dimensional oxalate-bridged anionic layer framework as the host and introduced ammonium cations and adipic acid molecules into the pores to increase proton concentration.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The result was one of the first instances of a MOF showing "superprotonic" conductivity (8 × 10−3 S/cm) at 25 °C and 98% relative humidity (RH).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] They later found that increasing the hydrophilic nature of the cations introduced into the pores could enhance proton conductivity even more.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] In this low temperature regime that is dependent on degree of hydration, it has also been shown that proton conductivity is heavily dependent on humidity levels.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] A high temperature anhydrous example is PCMOF2, which consists of sodium ions coordinated to a trisulfonated benzene derivative.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] To improve performance and allow for higher operating temperatures, water can be replaced as the proton carrier by less volatile imidazole or triazole molecules within the pores.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The maximum temperature achieved was 150 °C with an optimum conductivity of 5 × 10−4 S/cm, which is lower than other current electrolyte membranes.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] However, this model holds promise for its temperature regime, anhydrous conditions, and ability to control the quantity of guest molecules within the pores, all of which allowed for the tunability of proton conductivity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Additionally, the triazole-loaded PCMOF2 was incorporated into a H2/air membrane-electrode assembly and achieved an open circuit voltage of 1.18 V at 100 °C that was stable for 72 hours and managed to remain gas tight throughout testing.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] This was the first instance that proved MOFs could actually be implemented into functioning fuel cells, and the moderate potential difference showed that fuel crossover due to porosity was not an issue.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] To date, the highest proton conductivity achieved for a MOF electrolyte is 4.2 × 10−2 S/cm at 25 °C under humid conditions (98% RH), which is competitive with Nafion.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Some recent experiments have even successfully produced thin-film MOF membranes instead of the traditional bulk samples or single crystals, which is crucial for their industrial applicability.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Once MOFs are able to consistently achieve sufficient conductivity levels, mechanical strength, water stability, and simple processing, they have the potential to play an important role in PEMFCs in the near future.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] MOFs have also been targeted as potential replacements of platinum group metal (PGM) materials for electrode catalysts, although this research is still in the early stages of development.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] In PEMFCs, the oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) at the Pt cathode is significantly slower than the fuel oxidation reaction at the anode, and thus non-PGM and metal-free catalysts are being investigated as alternatives.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The high volumetric density, large pore surface areas, and openness of metal-ion sites in MOFs make them ideal candidates for catalyst precursors.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Despite promising catalytic abilities, the durability of these proposed MOF-based catalysts is currently less than desirable and the ORR mechanism in this context is still not completely understood.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] An important parameter for a fair catalyst comparison and benchmarking is the electrochemical surface area (ECSA) which accounts for the actual catalyst surface that actively partake in redox reactions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Its knowledge is necessary for the assessment of catalyst activity (e.g. specific activity, mass activity) and the design of the electrode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] One of the most used techniques for ECSA determination is CO stripping, which exploits the strong affinity of carbon monoxide to some metal electrocatalysts to assess the active area.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Examples of these approaches are given in the following sections.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] As mentioned above, platinum is by far the most effective element used for PEM fuel cell catalysts, and nearly all current PEM fuel cells use platinum particles on porous carbon supports to catalyze both hydrogen oxidation and oxygen reduction.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] However, due to their high cost, current Pt/C catalysts are not feasible for commercialization.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Department of Energy estimates that platinum-based catalysts will need to use roughly four times less platinum than is used in current PEM fuel cell designs in order to represent a realistic alternative to internal combustion engines.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Consequently, one main goal of catalyst design for PEM fuel cells is to increase the catalytic activity of platinum by a factor of four so that only one-fourth as much of the precious metal is necessary to achieve similar performance.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] One method of increasing the performance of platinum catalysts is to optimize the size and shape of the platinum particles.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Decreasing the particles' size alone increases the total surface area of catalyst available to participate in reactions per volume of platinum used, but recent studies have demonstrated additional ways to make further improvements to catalytic performance.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] For example, one study reports that high-index facets of platinum nanoparticles (that is Miller indexes with large integers, such as Pt (730)) provide a greater density of reactive sites for oxygen reduction than typical platinum nanoparticles.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Since the most common and effective catalyst, platinum, is extremely expensive, alternative processing is necessary to maximize electrochemical surface area and minimize loading.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Deposition of nanosized Pt particles onto carbon powder (Pt/C) provides a large Pt surface area while the carbon allows for electrical connection between the catalyst and the rest of the cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Platinum is so effective because it has high activity and bonds to the hydrogen just strongly enough to facilitate electron transfer but not inhibit the hydrogen from continuing to move around the cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] However, platinum is less active in the cathode oxygen reduction reaction.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] This necessitates the use of more platinum, increasing the cell's expense and thus feasibility.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Many potential catalyst choices are ruled out because of the extreme acidity of the cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The most effective ways of achieving the nanoscale Pt on carbon powder, which is currently the best option, are through vacuum deposition, sputtering, and electrodeposition.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The platinum particles are deposited onto carbon paper that is permeated with PTFE.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] However, there is an optimal thinness to this catalyst layer, which limits the lower cost limit.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Below 4 nm, Pt will form islands on the paper, limiting its activity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Above this thickness, the Pt will coat the carbon and be an effective catalyst.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] To further complicate things, Nafion cannot be infiltrated beyond 10 um, so using more Pt than this is an unnecessary expense.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Thus the amount and shape of the catalyst is limited by the constraints of other materials.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] A second method of increasing the catalytic activity of platinum is to alloy it with other metals.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] For example, it was recently shown that the Pt3Ni(111) surface has a higher oxygen reduction activity than pure Pt(111) by a factor of ten.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The authors attribute this dramatic performance increase to modifications to the electronic structure of the surface, reducing its tendency to bond to oxygen-containing ionic species present in PEM fuel cells and hence increasing the number of available sites for oxygen adsorption and reduction.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Further efficiencies can be realized using an Ultrasonic nozzle to apply the platinum catalyst to the electrolyte layer or to carbon paper under atmospheric conditions resulting in high efficiency spray.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Recent studies using inkjet printing to deposit the catalyst over the membrane have also shown high catalyst utilization due to the reduced thickness of the deposited catalyst layers.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Very recently, a new class of ORR electrocatalysts have been introduced in the case of Pt-M (M-Fe and Co) systems with an ordered intermetallic core encapsulated within a Pt-rich shell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] These **intermetallic core-shell (IMCS) nanocatalysts** were found to exhibit an enhanced activity and most importantly, an extended durability compared to many previous designs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] While the observed enhancement in the activities is ascribed to a strained lattice, the authors report that their findings on the degradation kinetics establish that the extended catalytic durability is attributable to a sustained atomic order.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The other popular approach to improving catalyst performance is to reduce its sensitivity to impurities in the fuel source, especially carbon monoxide (CO).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Presently, pure hydrogen gas is becoming economical to mass-produce by electrolysis.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] However, at the moment most hydrogen gas is produced by steam reforming light hydrocarbons, a process which produces a mixture of gases that also contains CO (1–3%), CO2 (19–25%), and N2 (25%).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Even tens of parts per million of CO can poison a pure platinum catalyst, so increasing platinum's resistance to CO is an active area of research.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] For example, one study reported that cube-shaped platinum nanoparticles with (100) facets displayed a fourfold increase in oxygen reduction activity compared to randomly faceted platinum nanoparticles of similar size.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The authors concluded that the (111) facets of the randomly shaped nanoparticles bonded more strongly to sulfate ions than the (100) facets, reducing the number of catalytic sites open to oxygen molecules.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The nanocubes they synthesized, in contrast, had almost exclusively (100) facets, which are known to interact with sulfate more weakly.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] This results in a significant increase of the electrochemical surface area, boosting the catalyst's oxygen reduction activity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] In addition, researchers have been investigating ways of reducing the CO content of hydrogen fuel before it enters a fuel cell as a possible way to avoid poisoning the catalysts.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] One recent study revealed that ruthenium-platinum core–shell nanoparticles are particularly effective at oxidizing CO to form CO2, a much less harmful fuel contaminant.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The mechanism that produces this effect is conceptually similar to that described for Pt3Ni above: the ruthenium core of the particle alters the electronic structure of the platinum surface, rendering it better able to catalyze the oxidation of CO.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The challenge for the viability of PEM fuel cells today still remains in their cost and stability.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The high cost can in large part be attributed to the use of the precious metal of platinum in the catalyst layer of PEM cells.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The electrocatalyst currently accounts for nearly half of the fuel cell stack cost.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Although the Pt loading of PEM fuel cells has been reduced by two orders of magnitude over the past decade, further reduction is necessary to make the technology economically viable for commercialization.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Department of Energy has been setting milestones for the development of fuel cells, targeting a durability of 5000 hours and a non-PGM catalyst ORR volumetric activity of 300 A cm−3.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Promising alternatives to Pt-based catalysts are Metal/Nitrogen/ Carbon-catalysts (M/N/C-catalysts).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] To achieve high power density, or output of power over surface area of the cell, a volumetric activity of at least 1/10 that of Pt-based catalysts must be met, along with good mass transport properties.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] While M/N/C-catalysts still demonstrate poorer volumetric activities than Pt-based catalysts, the reduced costs of such catalysts allows for greater loading to compensate.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] However, increasing the loading of M/N/C-catalysts also renders the catalytic layer thicker, impairing its mass transport properties.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] In other words, H2, O2, protons, and electrons have greater difficulty in migrating through the catalytic layer, decreasing the voltage output of the cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] While high microporosity of the M/N/C catalytic network results in high volumetric activity, improved mass transport properties are instead associated to macroporosity of the network.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] These M/N/C materials are synthesized using high temperature pyrolysis and other high temperature treatments of precursors containing the metal, nitrogen, and carbon.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Recently, researchers have developed a Fe/N/C catalyst derived from iron (II) acetate (FeAc), phenanthroline (Phen), and a metal-organic-framework (MOF) host.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The MOF is a Zn(II) zeolitic imidazolate framework (ZIF) called ZIF-8, which demonstrates a high microporous surface area and high nitrogen content conducive to ORR activity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The power density of the FeAc/Phen/ZIF-8-catalyst was found to be 0.75 W cm−2 at 0.6 V.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] This value is a significant improvement over the maximal 0.37 W cm−2 power density of previous M/N/C-catalysts and is much closer to matching the typical value of 1.0–1.2 W cm−2 for Pt-based catalysts with a Pt loading of 0.3 mg cm−2.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The catalyst also demonstrated a volumetric activity of 230 A·cm−3, the highest value for non-PGM catalysts to date, approaching the U.S.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] While the power density achieved by the novel FeAc/Phen/ZIF-8-catalyst is promising, its durability remains inadequate for commercial application.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] It is reported that the best durability exhibited by this catalyst still had a 15% drop in current density over 100 hours in H2/air.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Hence while the Fe-based non-PGM catalysts rival Pt-based catalysts in their electrocatalytic activity, there is still much work to be done in understanding their degradation mechanisms and improving their durability.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The major application of PEM fuel cells focuses on transportation primarily because of their potential impact on the environment, e.g. the control of emission of the green house gases (GHG).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Other applications include distributed/stationary and portable power generation.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Most major motor companies work solely on PEM fuel cells due to their high power density and excellent dynamic characteristics as compared with other types of fuel cells.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Due to their light weight, PEMFCs are most suited for transportation applications.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] PEMFCs for buses, which use compressed hydrogen for fuel, can operate at up to 40% efficiency.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Generally PEMFCs are implemented on buses over smaller cars because of the available volume to house the system and store the fuel.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Technical issues for transportation involve incorporation of PEMs into current vehicle technology and updating energy systems.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Full fuel cell vehicles are not advantageous if hydrogen is sourced from fossil fuels; however, they become beneficial when implemented as hybrids.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] There is potential for PEMFCs to be used for stationary power generation, where they provide 5 kW at 30% efficiency; however, they run into competition with other types of fuel cells, mainly SOFCs and MCFCs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Whereas PEMFCs generally require high purity hydrogen for operation, other fuel cell types can run on methane and are thus more flexible systems.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Therefore, PEMFCs are best for small scale systems until economically scalable pure hydrogen is available.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Furthermore, PEMFCs have the possibility of replacing batteries for portable electronics, though integration of the hydrogen supply is a technical challenge particularly without a convenient location to store it within the device.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Before the invention of PEM fuel cells, existing fuel cell types such as solid-oxide fuel cells were only applied in extreme conditions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Such fuel cells also required very expensive materials and could only be used for stationary applications due to their size.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] These issues were addressed by the PEM fuel cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The PEM fuel cell was invented in the early 1960s by Willard Thomas Grubb and Leonard Niedrach of General Electric.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Initially, sulfonated polystyrene membranes were used for electrolytes, but they were replaced in 1966 by Nafion ionomer, which proved to be superior in performance and durability to sulfonated polystyrene.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] PEM fuel cells were used in the NASA Gemini series of spacecraft, but they were replaced by Alkaline fuel cells in the Apollo program and in the Space Shuttle.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] General Electric continued working on PEM cells and in the mid-1970s developed PEM water electrolysis technology for undersea life support, leading to the US Navy Oxygen Generating Plant.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The British Royal Navy adopted this technology in early 1980s for their submarine fleet.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] In the late 1980s and early 1990s, Los Alamos National Lab and Texas A&M University experimented with ways to reduce the amount of platinum required for PEM cells.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Parallel with Pratt and Whitney Aircraft, General Electric developed the first proton exchange membrane fuel cells (PEMFCs) for the Gemini space missions in the early 1960s.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The first mission to use PEMFCs was Gemini V.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] However, the Apollo space missions and subsequent Apollo-Soyuz, Skylab and Space Shuttle missions used fuel cells based on Bacon's design, developed by Pratt and Whitney Aircraft.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Extremely expensive materials were used and the fuel cells required very pure hydrogen and oxygen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Early fuel cells tended to require inconveniently high operating temperatures that were a problem in many applications.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] However, fuel cells were seen to be desirable due to the large amounts of fuel available (hydrogen and oxygen).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Despite their success in space programs, fuel cell systems were limited to space missions and other special applications, where high cost could be tolerated.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] It was not until the late 1980s and early 1990s that fuel cells became a real option for wider application base.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] Several pivotal innovations, such as low platinum catalyst loading and thin film electrodes, drove the cost of fuel cells down, making development of PEMFC systems more realistic.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] However, there is significant debate as to whether hydrogen fuel cells will be a realistic technology for use in automobiles or other vehicles.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] (See hydrogen economy.) A large part of PEMFC production is for the Toyota Mirai.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/proton-exchange-membrane-fuel-cell] The US Department of Energy estimates a 2016 price at $53/kW if 500,000 units per year were made.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] A **solid oxide fuel cell** (or **SOFC**) is an electrochemical conversion device that produces electricity directly from oxidizing a fuel.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Fuel cells are characterized by their electrolyte material; the SOFC has a solid oxide or ceramic electrolyte.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Advantages of this class of fuel cells include high combined heat and power efficiency, long-term stability, fuel flexibility, low emissions, and relatively low cost.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The largest disadvantage is the high operating temperature, which results in longer start-up times and mechanical and chemical compatibility issues.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Solid oxide fuel cells are a class of fuel cells characterized by using a solid oxide material as the electrolyte.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] SOFCs use a solid oxide electrolyte to conduct negative oxygen ions from the cathode to the anode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The electrochemical oxidation of the hydrogen, carbon monoxide or other organic intermediates by oxygen ions thus occurs on the anode side.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] More recently, proton-conducting SOFCs (PC-SOFC) have been developed to transport protons instead of oxygen ions through the electrolyte with the advantage of running at lower temperatures than traditional SOFCs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] They operate at very high temperatures, typically between 600 and 1,000 °C.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] At these temperatures, SOFCs do not require expensive platinum group metals catalysts, as is currently necessary for lower temperature fuel cells such as PEMFCs, and are not vulnerable to carbon monoxide catalyst poisoning.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] However, vulnerability to sulfur poisoning has been widely observed, and the sulfur must be removed before entering the cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] For lower-quality fuels, such as gasified biomass, coal, or biogas, fuel processing becomes increasingly complex and, consequently, more expensive.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The gasification process, which transforms the raw material into a gaseous state suitable for fuel cells, can generate significant quantities of compounds like methane and toluene, as well as larger polyaromatic and short-chain hydrocarbon compounds.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] These substances can lead to carbon buildup in SOFCs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The expenses associated with reforming and desulfurization are comparable in magnitude to the cost of the fuel cell itself.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] These factors become especially critical for systems with lower power output or greater portability requirements.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Solid oxide fuel cells have a wide variety of applications, from using them as auxiliary power units in vehicles to stationary power generation with outputs from 100 W to 2 MW.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] In 2009, the Australian company, Ceramic Fuel Cells, successfully achieved an efficiency of an SOFC device up to the previously theoretical mark of 60%.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The higher operating temperature makes SOFCs suitable for application with heat engine energy recovery devices or combined heat and power, further increasing overall fuel efficiency.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Because of these high temperatures, light hydrocarbon fuels, such as methane, propane, and butane, can be internally reformed within the anode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] SOFCs can also be fueled by externally reforming heavier hydrocarbons, such as gasoline, diesel, jet fuel (JP-8) or biofuels.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Such reformates are mixtures of hydrogen, carbon monoxide, carbon dioxide, steam and methane, formed by reacting the hydrocarbon fuels with air or steam in a device upstream of the SOFC anode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] SOFC power systems can increase efficiency by using the heat from the exothermic electrochemical oxidation within the fuel cell for an endothermic steam reforming process.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Solid fuels, such as coal and biomass, may also be gasified to form syngas suitable for fueling SOFCs in integrated gasification fuel cell power cycles.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Thermal expansion demands a uniform and well-regulated heating process at startup.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] SOFC stacks with planar geometry require an hour to heat to operating temperature.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Micro-tubular fuel cell design geometries promise much faster start-up times, typically in the order of minutes.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Unlike most other types of fuel cells, SOFCs can have multiple geometries.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The planar fuel cell design geometry is the typical sandwich-type geometry employed by most types of fuel cells, where the electrolyte is sandwiched between the electrodes.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] SOFCs can also be made in tubular geometries where either air or fuel is passed through the inside of the tube, and the other gas is passed along the outside of the tube.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The tubular design is advantageous because it is much easier to seal air from the fuel.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The performance of the planar design is currently better than the performance of the tubular design, however, because the planar design has a lower resistance comparatively.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Other geometries of SOFCs include modified planar fuel cell designs (MPC or MPSOFC), where a wave-like structure replaces the traditional flat configuration of the planar cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Such designs are highly promising because they share the advantages of both planar cells (low resistance) and tubular cells.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] A solid oxide fuel cell is made up of four layers, three of which are ceramics (hence the name).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] A single cell consisting of these four layers stacked together is typically only a few millimeters thick.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Hundreds of these cells are then connected in series to form what most people refer to as an "SOFC stack".
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The ceramics used in SOFCs do not become electrically and ionically active until they reach very high temperatures.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] As a consequence, the stacks have to run at temperatures ranging from 500 to 1,000 °C.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Reduction of oxygen into oxygen ions occurs at the cathode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] These ions can then diffuse through the solid oxide electrolyte to the anode where they can electrochemically oxidize the fuel.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] In this reaction, water byproduct and two electrons are given off.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] These electrons then flow through an external circuit where they can do work.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The cycle then repeats as those electrons enter the cathode material again.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] By using internal reforming (converting methane into hydrogen internally), lower cooling requirements are needed, helping decrease the complexity and costs of the balance of plant.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The ceramic anode layer must be very porous to allow the fuel to flow towards the electrolyte.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Consequently, granular matter is often selected for anode fabrication procedures.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Like the cathode, it must conduct electrons.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] A capacity for ionic conductivity is an additional advantage.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The anode's smaller polarization losses allows a comparatively thicker layer to provide the cell's mechanical support.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The electrochemical function of the anode is to facilitate the oxidation of a fuel, typically hydrogen, to produce heat, water and electricity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Where a light hydrocarbon (e.g. methane) is used, the anode can also act as a catalyst for steam reformation of the fuel.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] This provides another operational benefit to the fuel cell stack because the reforming reaction is endothermic, which cools the stack internally.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The most common material used is a cermet made of nickel mixed with the ceramic material used for the electrolyte in that particular cell, typically YSZ (yttria stabilized zirconia).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Anodes can be produced by tape casting, using slurry prepared by sonication.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] This low-impact mixing allows for the effective combination of NiO-YSZ slurries in about 30 minutes, much faster than conventional ball milling (72 hours).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The nanomaterial-based catalysts help stop the grain growth of nickel.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Larger grains of nickel would reduce the contact area that ions can be conducted through, which would lower the cell's efficiency.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Perovskite materials (mixed ionic/electronic conducting ceramics) have been shown to produce a power density of 0.6 W/cm2 at 0.7 V at 800 °C which is possible because they have the ability to overcome a larger activation energy.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] However, a few disadvantages are associated with YSZ as an anode material.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Ni coarsening, carbon deposition, reduction-oxidation instability, and sulfur poisoning are the main obstacles limiting the long-term stability of Ni-YSZ.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Ni coarsening refers to the evolution of Ni particles in YSZ, which grows larger in grain size, decreasing the surface area for the catalytic reaction.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Carbon deposition occurs when carbon atoms, formed by hydrocarbon pyrolysis or CO disproportionation, deposit on the Ni catalytic surface.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Carbon deposition becomes important, especially when hydrocarbon fuels, i.e., methane and syngas, are used.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The high operating temperature of SOFC and the oxidizing environment facilitate the oxidation of Ni catalyst through the reaction Ni + 1⁄2 O2 = NiO.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The oxidation reaction of Ni reduces the electrocatalytic activity and conductivity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Moreover, the density difference between Ni and NiO causes volume change on the anode surface, potentially leading to mechanical failure.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Sulfur poisoning arises when fuel such as natural gas, gasoline, or diesel is used.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Again, due to the high affinity between sulfur compounds (H2S, (CH3)2S) and the metal catalyst, even the smallest impurities of sulfur compounds in the feed stream could deactivate the Ni catalyst on the YSZ surface.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Current research is focused on reducing or replacing Ni content in the anode to improve long-term performance.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The modified Ni-YSZ containing other materials, including CeO2, Y2O3, La2O3, MgO, TiO2, Ru, Co, etc., have been invented to resist sulfur poisoning, but the improvement is limited due to the rapid initial degradation.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Copper-based cermet anode is considered a solution to carbon deposition because it is inert to carbon and stable under typical SOFC oxygen partial pressures (pO2).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Cu-Co bimetallic anodes show a great resistance to carbon deposition after exposure to pure CH4 at 800C.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Cu-CeO2-YSZ exhibits a higher electrochemical oxidation rate over Ni-YSZ when running on CO and syngas.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] It can achieve even higher performance using CO than H2, after adding a cobalt co-catalyst.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Oxide anodes, including zirconia-based fluorite and perovskites, are also used to replace Ni-ceramic anodes for carbon resistance.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Chromite, i.e., La0.8Sr0.2Cr0.5Mn0.5O3 (LSCM), is used as anodes and exhibited comparable performance against Ni–YSZ cermet anodes.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] LSCM is further improved by impregnating Cu and sputtering Pt as the current collector.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The electrolyte is a dense layer of ceramic that conducts oxygen ions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Its electronic conductivity must be kept as low as possible to prevent losses from leakage currents.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The high operating temperatures of SOFCs allow the kinetics of oxygen ion transport to be sufficient for good performance.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] However, as the operating temperature approaches the lower limit for SOFCs at around 600 °C, the electrolyte begins to have large ionic transport resistances and affect the performance.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Popular electrolyte materials include yttria-stabilized zirconia (YSZ) (often the 8% form 8YSZ), scandia stabilized zirconia (ScSZ) (usually 9 mol% Sc2O3 – 9ScSZ) and gadolinium doped ceria (GDC).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The electrolyte material has a crucial influence on the cell performance.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Detrimental reactions between YSZ electrolytes and modern cathodes such as lanthanum strontium cobalt ferrite (LSCF) have been found, and can be prevented by thin (<100 nm) ceria diffusion barriers.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] If the conductivity for oxygen ions in SOFC can remain high even at lower temperatures (current target in research ~500 °C), material choices for SOFC will broaden, and many existing problems can be solved.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] In 2025, Kyushu University researchers successfully re-engineering an SOFC electrolyte to develop one that is operational at 300 °C (500 °F).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The lower-temperature innovation may facilitate lower-cost SOFCs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Termed a "scandium superhighway", the significantly lower temperature is made viable via "a high-density network of Sc–O bonds in scandium-doped" barium stannate (BSO) and barium titanate (BTO) ceramics, which cuts the proton migration barrier, unlocking rapid proton transport.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Findings were published in August 2025, in the peer-reviewed materials science and engineering journal, *Nature Materials*.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The cathode, or air electrode, is a thin porous layer on the electrolyte where oxygen reduction occurs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Cathode materials must be, at a minimum, electrically conductive.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Currently, lanthanum strontium manganite (LSM) is the cathode material of choice for commercial use because of its compatibility with doped zirconia electrolytes.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Mechanically, it has a similar coefficient of thermal expansion to YSZ and thus limits stress buildup because of CTE mismatch.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Also, LSM has low levels of chemical reactivity with YSZ, which extends the lifetime of the materials.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Unfortunately, LSM is a poor ionic conductor, so the electrochemically active reaction is limited to the triple phase boundary (TPB) where the electrolyte, air and electrode meet.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] LSM works well as a cathode at high temperatures, but its performance quickly falls as the operating temperature is below 800 °C.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] To increase the reaction zone beyond the TPB, a potential cathode material must be able to conduct both electrons and oxygen ions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Composite cathodes consisting of LSM YSZ have been used to increase this triple-phase boundary length.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Mixed ionic/electronic conducting (MIEC) ceramics, such as perovskite LSCF, are also being researched for use in intermediate temperature SOFCs as they are more active and can make up for the increase in the activation energy of the reaction.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The interconnect can be either a metallic or ceramic component between each cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Its purpose is to connect each cell in series, so that the voltage each cell generates can be combined.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Because the interconnect is exposed to the cell's oxidizing and reducing side at high temperatures, it must be extremely stable.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] For this reason, ceramics have been traditionally used as interconnect materials.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] However, these ceramic interconnect materials are very expensive when compared to metals.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Nowadays, lower operating temperatures (600–850 °C) are common, and almost all SOFC designs use ferritic stainless steel (Fe-Cr Steel with bcc structure).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Alternatively, a Cr based Cr-5Fe-1Y2O3 alloy is used in some designs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Ceramic-metal composites called "cermet" are also under consideration, as they have demonstrated thermal stability at high temperatures and excellent electrical conductivity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Polarizations, or overpotentials, are losses in voltage due to imperfections in materials, microstructure, and design of the fuel cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] In SOFCs, it is often important to focus on the ohmic and concentration polarizations since high operating temperatures experience little activation polarization.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] However, as the lower limit of SOFC operating temperature is approached (~600 °C), these polarizations do become important.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Above mentioned equation is used for determining the SOFC voltage (in fact for fuel cell voltage in general).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] This approach results in good agreement with particular experimental data (for which adequate factors were obtained) and poor agreement for other than original experimental working parameters.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Moreover, most of the equations used require the addition of numerous factors which are difficult or impossible to determine.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] It makes very difficult any optimizing process of the SOFC working parameters as well as design architecture configuration selection.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] This method was validated and found suitable for optimization and sensitivity studies in plant-level modelling of various systems with solid oxide fuel cells.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] With this mathematical description, it is possible to account for different properties of the SOFC.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Many parameters which impact cell working conditions, e.g., electrolyte material, electrolyte thickness, cell temperature, inlet and outlet gas compositions at anode and cathode, and electrode porosity, just to name some.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The flow in these systems is often calculated using the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Ohmic losses in an SOFC result from ionic conductivity through the electrolyte and electrical resistance offered to the flow of electrons in the external electrical circuit.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] This is inherently a material property of the crystal structure and atoms involved.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] However, to maximize the ionic conductivity, several methods can be used.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Firstly, operating at higher temperatures can significantly decrease these ohmic losses.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Substitutional doping methods to further refine the crystal structure and control defect concentrations can also play a significant role in increasing the conductivity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Another way to decrease ohmic resistance is to decrease the thickness of the electrolyte layer.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] where: $\delta$ – electrolyte thickness, and $\sigma$ – ionic conductivity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] where: $\sigma _{0}$ and E – factors depended on electrolyte materials, T – electrolyte temperature, and R – ideal gas constant.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The concentration polarization is the result of practical limitations on mass transport within the cell and represents the voltage loss due to spatial variations in reactant concentration at the chemically active sites.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] This situation can be caused when the reactants are consumed by the electrochemical reaction faster than they can diffuse into the porous electrode, and can also be caused by variation in bulk flow composition.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The latter is due to the fact that the consumption of reacting species in the reactant flows causes a drop in reactant concentration as it travels along the cell, which causes a drop in the local potential near the tail end of the cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The concentration polarization occurs in both the anode and cathode.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The anode can be particularly problematic, as the oxidation of the hydrogen produces steam, which further dilutes the fuel stream as it travels along the length of the cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] This polarization can be mitigated by reducing the reactant utilization fraction or increasing the electrode porosity, but these approaches each have significant design trade-offs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The activation polarization is the result of the kinetics involved with the electrochemical reactions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Each reaction has a certain activation barrier that must be overcome to proceed, and this barrier leads to the polarization.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The activation barrier is the result of many complex electrochemical reaction steps where typically the rate limiting step is responsible for the polarization.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The polarization can be modified by microstructural optimization.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The Triple Phase Boundary (TPB) length, which is the length where porous, ionic and electronically conducting pathways all meet, directly relates to the electrochemically active length in the cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The larger the length, the more reactions can occur and thus the less the activation polarization.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Optimization of TPB length can be done by processing conditions to affect microstructure or by materials selection to use a mixed ionic/electronic conductor to further increase TPB length.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Current SOFC research focuses heavily on optimizing cell performance while maintaining acceptable mechanical properties because optimized performance often compromises mechanical properties.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Nevertheless, mechanical failure represents a significant problem to SOFC operation.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The presence of various kinds of load and Thermal stress during operation requires high mechanical strength.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Additional stresses associated with changes in gas atmosphere, leading to reduction or oxidation also cannot be avoided in prolonged operation.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] When electrode layers delaminate or crack, conduction pathways are lost, leading to a redistribution of current density and local changes in temperature.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] These local temperature deviations, in turn, lead to increased thermal strains, which propagate cracks and Delamination.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Additionally, when electrolytes crack, separation of fuel and air is no longer guaranteed, which further endangers the continuous operation of the cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Since SOFCs require materials with high oxygen conductivity, thermal stresses provide a significant problem.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The Coefficient of thermal expansion in mixed ionic-electronic perovskites can be directly related to oxygen vacancy concentration, which is also related to ionic conductivity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Thus, thermal stresses increase in direct correlation with improved cell performance.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Additionally, however, the temperature dependence of oxygen vacancy concentration means that the CTE is not a linear property, which further complicates measurements and predictions.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Just as thermal stresses increase as cell performance improves through improved ionic conductivity, the fracture toughness of the material also decreases as cell performance increases.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] This is because, to increase reaction sites, porous ceramics are preferable.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] However, as shown in the equation below, fracture toughness decreases as porosity increases.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Thus, porosity must be carefully engineered to maximize reaction kinetics while maintaining an acceptable fracture toughness.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Since fracture toughness represents the ability of pre-existing cracks or pores to propagate, a potentially more useful metric is the failure stress of a material, as this depends on sample dimensions instead of crack diameter.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Failure stresses in SOFCs can also be evaluated using a ring-on ring biaxial stress test.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] This type of test is generally preferred, as sample edge quality does not significantly impact measurements.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The determination of the sample's failure stress is shown in the equation below.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] However, this equation is not valid for deflections exceeding 1/2h, making it less applicable for thin samples, which are of great interest in SOFCs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Therefore, while this method does not require knowledge of crack or pore size, it must be used with great caution and is more applicable to support layers in SOFCs than active layers.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] In addition to failure stresses and fracture toughness, modern fuel cell designs that favor mixed ionic electronic conductors (MIECs), Creep (deformation) pose another great problem, as MIEC electrodes often operate at temperatures exceeding half of the melting temperature.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] As a result, diffusion creep must also be considered.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] To properly model creep strain rates, knowledge of Microstructure is therefore of significant importance.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] DOE target requirements are 40,000 hours of service for stationary fuel cell applications and greater than 5,000 hours for transportation systems (fuel cell vehicles) at a factory cost of $40/kW for a 10 kW coal-based system without additional requirements.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Lifetime effects (phase stability, thermal expansion compatibility, element migration, conductivity and aging) must be addressed.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The Solid State Energy Conversion Alliance 2008 (interim) target for overall degradation per 1,000 hours is 4.0%.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Research is going now in the direction of lower-temperature SOFCs (600 °C).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Low temperature systems can reduce costs by reducing insulation, materials, start-up and degradation-related costs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] With higher operating temperatures, the temperature gradient increases the severity of thermal stresses, which affects materials cost and life of the system.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] An intermediate temperature system (650-800 °C) would enable the use of cheaper metallic materials with better mechanical properties and thermal conductivity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] New developments in nano-scale electrolyte structures have been shown to bring down operating temperatures to around 350 °C, which would enable the use of even cheaper steel and elastomeric/polymeric components.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Lowering operating temperatures has the added benefit of increased efficiency.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Theoretical fuel cell efficiency increases with decreasing temperature.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] For example, the efficiency of a SOFC using CO as fuel increases from 63% to 81% when decreasing the system temperature from 900 °C to 350 °C.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Research is also under way to improve the fuel flexibility of SOFCs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] While stable operation has been achieved on a variety of hydrocarbon fuels, these cells typically rely on external fuel processing.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] In the case of natural gas, the fuel is either externally or internally reformed and the sulfur compounds are removed.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] These processes add to the cost and complexity of SOFC systems.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Work is under way at a number of institutions to improve the stability of anode materials for hydrocarbon oxidation and, therefore, relax the requirements for fuel processing and decrease SOFC balance of plant costs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Research is also going on in reducing start-up time to be able to implement SOFCs in mobile applications.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] This can be partially achieved by lowering operating temperatures, which is the case for proton-exchange membrane fuel cell (PEMFCs).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Due to their fuel flexibility, they may run on partially reformed diesel, and this makes SOFCs interesting as auxiliary power units (APU) in refrigerated trucks.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Specifically, Delphi Automotive Systems are developing an SOFC that will power auxiliary units in automobiles and tractor-trailers, while BMW has recently stopped a similar project.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] A high-temperature SOFC will generate all of the needed electricity to allow the engine to be smaller and more efficient.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The SOFC would run on the same gasoline or diesel as the engine and would keep the air conditioning unit and other necessary electrical systems running while the engine shuts off when not needed (e.g., at a stop light or truck stop).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Rolls-Royce is developing solid-oxide fuel cells produced by screen printing onto inexpensive ceramic materials.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Rolls-Royce Fuel Cell Systems Ltd is developing an SOFC gas turbine hybrid system fueled by natural gas for power generation applications in the order of a megawatt (e.g.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] 3D printing is being explored as a possible manufacturing technique that could be used to make SOFC manufacturing easier by the Shah Lab at Northwestern University.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] This manufacturing technique would allow SOFC cell structure to be more flexible, which could lead to more efficient designs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] This process could work in the production of any part of the cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The 3D printing process works by combining about 80% ceramic particles with 20% binders and solvents, and then converting that slurry into an ink that can be fed into a 3D printer.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Some of the solvent is very volatile, so the ceramic ink solidifies almost immediately.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Not all of the solvent evaporates, so the ink maintains some flexibility before it is fired at high temperature to densify it.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] This flexibility allows the cells to be fired in a circular shape that would increase the surface area over which electrochemical reactions can occur, which increases the efficiency of the cell.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Also, the 3D printing technique allows the cell layers to be printed on top of each other instead of having to go through separate manufacturing and stacking steps.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The thickness is easy to control, and layers can be made in the exact size and shape that is needed, so waste is minimized.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Ceres Power Ltd. has developed a low cost and low temperature (500–600 degrees) SOFC stack using cerium gadolinium oxide (CGO) in place of current industry standard ceramic, yttria stabilized zirconia (YSZ), which allows the use of stainless steel to support the ceramic.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Solid Cell Inc. has developed a unique, low-cost cell architecture that combines properties of planar and tubular designs, along with a Cr-free cermet interconnect.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The high temperature electrochemistry center (HITEC) at the University of Florida, Gainesville is focused on studying ionic transport, electrocatalytic phenomena and microstructural characterization of ion conducting materials.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] SiEnergy Systems, a Harvard spin-off company, has demonstrated the first macro-scale thin-film solid-oxide fuel cell that can operate at 500 degrees.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] A solid oxide electrolyser cell (SOEC) is a solid oxide fuel cell set in regenerative mode for the electrolysis of water with a solid oxide, or ceramic, electrolyte to produce oxygen and hydrogen gas.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] SOECs can also be used to do electrolysis of CO2 to produce CO and oxygen or even co-electrolysis of water and CO2 to produce syngas and oxygen.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] SOFCs that operate in an intermediate temperature (IT) range, meaning between 600 and 800 °C, are named ITSOFCs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Because of the high degradation rates and materials costs incurred at temperatures in excess of 900 °C, it is economically more favorable to operate SOFCs at lower temperatures.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The push for high-performance ITSOFCs is currently the topic of much research and development.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] One area of focus is the cathode material.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] It is thought that the oxygen reduction reaction is responsible for much of the loss in performance so the catalytic activity of the cathode is being studied and enhanced through various techniques, including catalyst impregnation.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The research on NdCrO3 proves it to be a potential cathode material for the cathode of ITSOFC since it is thermochemically stable within the temperature range.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Another area of focus is electrolyte materials.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] To make SOFCs competitive in the market, ITSOFCs are pushing towards lower operational temperature by use of alternative new materials.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] However, efficiency and stability of the materials limit their feasibility.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] One choice for the electrolyte new materials is the ceria-salt ceramic composites (CSCs).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The two-phase CSC electrolytes GDC (gadolinium-doped ceria) and SDC (samaria-doped ceria)-MCO3 (M=Li, Na, K, single or mixture of carbonates) can reach the power density of 300-800 mW*cm−2.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Low-temperature solid oxide fuel cells (LT-SOFCs), operating lower than 650 °C, are of great interest for future research because the high operating temperature is currently what restricts the development and deployment of SOFCs.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] A low-temperature SOFC is more reliable due to smaller thermal mismatch and easier sealing.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Additionally, a lower temperature requires less insulation and therefore has a lower cost.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Cost is further lowered due to wider material choices for interconnects and compressive nonglass/ceramic seals.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Perhaps most importantly, at a lower temperature, SOFCs can be started more rapidly and with less energy, which lends itself to uses in portable and transportable applications.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] As temperature decreases, the maximum theoretical fuel cell efficiency increases, in contrast to the Carnot cycle.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] For example, the maximum theoretical efficiency of an SOFC using CO as a fuel increases from 63% at 900 °C to 81% at 350 °C.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] This is a materials issue, particularly for the electrolyte in the SOFC.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] YSZ is the most commonly used electrolyte because of its superior stability, despite not having the highest conductivity.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Currently, the thickness of YSZ electrolytes is a minimum of ~10 μm due to deposition methods, and this requires a temperature above 700 °C.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Therefore, low-temperature SOFCs are only possible with higher conductivity electrolytes.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Various alternatives that could be successful at low temperature include gadolinium-doped ceria (GDC) and erbia-cation-stabilized bismuth (ERB).
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] They have superior ionic conductivity at lower temperatures, but this comes at the expense of lower thermodynamic stability.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] CeO2 electrolytes become electronically conductive and Bi2O3 electrolytes decompose to metallic Bi under the reducing fuel environment.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] To combat this, researchers created a functionally graded ceria/bismuth-oxide bilayered electrolyte where the GDC layer on the anode side protects the ESB layer from decomposing while the ESB on the cathode side blocks the leakage current through the GDC layer.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] This leads to near-theoretical open-circuit potential (OPC) with two highly conductive electrolytes, that by themselves would not have been sufficiently stable for the application.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] This bilayer proved to be stable for 1400 hours of testing at 500 °C and showed no indication of interfacial phase formation or thermal mismatch.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] While this makes strides towards lowering the operating temperature of SOFCs, it also opens doors for future research to try and understand this mechanism.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Researchers at the Georgia Institute of Technology dealt with the instability of BaCeO3 differently.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] They replaced a desired fraction of Ce in BaCeO3 with Zr to form a solid solution that exhibits proton conductivity, but also chemical and thermal stability over the range of conditions relevant to fuel cell operation.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] A new specific composition, Ba(Zr0.1Ce0.7Y0.2)O3-δ (BZCY7) that displays the highest ionic conductivity of all known electrolyte materials for SOFC applications.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] This electrolyte was fabricated by dry-pressing powders, which allowed for the production of crack free films thinner than 15 μm.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] The implementation of this simple and cost-effective fabrication method may enable significant cost reductions in SOFC fabrication.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] However, this electrolyte operates at higher temperatures than the bilayered electrolyte model, closer to 600 °C rather than 500 °C.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Currently, given the state of the field for LT-SOFCs, progress in the electrolyte would reap the most benefits, but research into potential anode and cathode materials would also lead to useful results, and has started to be discussed more frequently in literature.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] An SOFC-GT system is one which comprises a solid oxide fuel cell combined with a gas turbine.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Such systems have been evaluated by Siemens Westinghouse and Rolls-Royce as a means to achieve higher operating efficiencies by running the SOFC under pressure.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] SOFC-GT systems typically include anodic and/or cathodic atmosphere recirculation, thus increasing efficiency.
[src:fuel-cell-chemistry/solid-oxide-fuel-cell] Theoretically, the combination of the SOFC and gas turbine can give result in high overall (electrical and thermal) efficiency.
